<html>
<head>
<title>Global Change and Environmental Education Resources</title>
</head>
<body>
<a name=#A> </a>
<a href = "http://gcrio.ciesin.org/"><img align = bottom src = "/gifs/gcrio-header.gif"></a><br>
<hr><br>
<p align=center>
<h1>Global Change and Environmental Education Resources</h1>
<p align=left>
Multidisciplinary and international in scope, this comprehensive collection of resources was selected for their relevance to global change and environmental education. Included are a wide range of resources in a variety of formats for 
educators and students at all levels (k-12 and higher education), librarians,
citizens and community groups.
<p align=left>

<ul>
<li><a href="agci-home.html">Aspen Global Change Institute</a><br>
Aspen's mission is to "further understanding of Earth Systems through interdisciplinary science meetings, publications, and educational programs about global change science." This affiliated program of GCRIO includes searchable abstracts,
a quarterly update for educators, and publications and videos for K-12 .<p>

<li><a href="http://www.clearinghouse.net/tree/envir.html">Clearinghouse of Subject-Oriented Internet
Resource Guides: Environment</a><br>
Value-added guides which "identify, describe, and evaluate" Internet-based
environmental resources and cover 40+ topics including energy, earth
sciences, forestry, sustainable
development, remote sensing, and environmental ethics, policy and law.<p>

<li><a href="http://www.cfe.cornell.edu">Cornell Center for the Environment</a><br>
A significant environmental site that combines research, teaching and outreach.
Includes notable environmental sites in the<a href="http://www.cfe.cornell.edu/sow.html"> E-Site of the
Week</a> postings.<p> 

<li><a href="/educ/EarthEducation.html">Earth Education Site</a><br> 
Educators and students will want to bookmark this one! The scope and arrangement of this collection make navigation easy and provide links to lesson plans,
 classroom activities and resources(some free!), catalogs, professional
 organizations, federal agencies, non governmental organizations, conferences,
 libraries and other educational tools. <a href="/educ/Features.html">Features</a>, a
series of articles, connects to exceptional teachers, cutting edge scientists
and researchers or trailblazing environmentalists to augment global change and
environmental education. Future plans include an interactive capability that
will enhance global communication and foster global education.<p> 

<li><a href="edu.mailing.html">Electronic Mailing Lists for Global and Environmental Change Education</a><br>
Compiled to provide easy access, these lists are useful discussion forums that
address topical areas.<p>

<li><a href="opportunities.html">Fellowships, Grants, and Funding Opportunities</a><br>
Various sources of essential information(including federal agencies) involved in pursuing educational and research opportunities and grants.<p>

<li><a href="gen.pub.html">General Public and Community Groups</a><br>
For private citizens, consumers, public interest and community groups seeking information about the human impacts of global and environmental change.<p>

<li><a href="http://www.mbnet.mb.ca/lucas/gcg/">Global Change Game</a><br>
This environmental education project was invented by students at the University
of Manitoba in 1991 and is a challenging, energy-demanding, fast-paced creative
activity that explores
major global problems.<p>

<li><a href="/gwcc/toc.html">Global Warming and Climate Change</a><br>
A publication prepared by researchers in the Department of
Engineering and Public Policy at Carnegie Mellon University to explain the
issue of global warming and climate change to a general audience.  Issues
addressed include:  The science of global warming; the potential impacts of
climate change, and the range of policy responses to the threat of climate
change.
<p>

<li><!-- a href=LITERATURE_LINK -->Literature Link (coming soon)<br>
Tables of Contents and Current Awareness Services provide an invaluable link to recently published periodical literature. The primary focus of these selected tables of contents and citations to articles and materials is current subject coverage of Global and Environmental Change from journals, magazines and government publications.<p> 

<li><a href="http://sedac.ciesin.org/pidb/pidb-home.html">Environmental Treaties and Resource Indicators (ENTRI)</a><br>
The Consortium for International Earth Science Information Network (CIESIN)
provides online browsing and searching of 120 treaties(full text, summaries, and
the status) and other international agreements related to global environmental
change. ENTRI covers nine global environmental issues: global climate change,
stratospheric ozone depletion, transboundary air pollution, land use/land cover change and desertification,
conservation of biological diversity, deforestation, oceans and their living
resources, trade and the environment, and population.<p> 

<li><a href="http://www.vims.edu/adv/gc/gclist.html">VIMS (Virginia Sea Grant/Virginia Institute of Marine
Science) Sea Grant Global Change Education</a><br>
Focusing on Global Change and Sustainability, this site includes:  
An Educators' Page with links to teaching resources, lesson plans and
activities; Student global change papers; and, a Global Change and
Sustainabililty Index with reading lists, overviews and fact sheets.<p>

<li><a href="http://www.wri.org/">World Resources Institute (WRI) Environmental
Education</a><br>
WRI presents a wealth of resources in many formats
from full-text online access to videos, slides, and guides that include lesson
plans, overhead transparency
masters, and student exercises.
WRI addresses both local and global environmental issues by
adaptating teaching materials to local needs(Mexico, India,
Europe, Australia, Vietnam, and Japan with more countries to come) and the
production of
foreign language adaptations of Teachers Guides.
World Resources 1996-97, an excellent reference
source in full-text, offers "projections based on scientific studies, scenarios, and
quantitative models to document future environmental challenges" and 
"contains more than
150 tables, charts, maps, and figures with essential environmental and natural
resources data for nearly every
country in the world."
The projected development(Spring 1997) of DataScape, an interactive software
that will allow "students and professionals to explore global resource data on
the environment, offers promise for future activities.<p> 
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.gcrio.org/">GCRIO Home Page</a>      |      <a href=#A>Top 
of This Page</a>      <p align =center>
