<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Earth Pulse News Spring 1996 - Chemical pollution as a global 
phenomenon    </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
      
           <CENTER>
             <H2>       Chemical pollution as a global phenomenon   </H2>
            </CENTER>

On remote Midway atoll in the North Pacific, researchers have found high 
levels of DDT compounds, PCBs, and dioxin-like compounds in albatross 
adults, chicks and eggs.  They have also found the effects of exposure to these 
chemicals, including deformed embryos, eggshell thinning and a 3% drop in 
nest productivity.  The results are cause for concern because of the potential 
for greater harm to albatrosses and other species, reports <I>The New York 
Times, </I> 12 March 1996.  The chemicals and effects are the same as those 
that caused crashes in the populations of bald eagles, brown pelicans and 
peregrine falcons 30 years ago in North America.

<P>

"Concentrations of persistent chemicals in black-footed albatrosses on 
Midway are nearly as great as current levels in bald eagles from the highly 
contaminated Great Lakes," says Dr. James Ludwig, a bird population 
ecologist.  He says that the pollutants in the bird's diet are probably coming 
from India, Southeast Asia and Japan.  Toxicologist Dr. John Giesy says, 
"While albatrosses feed near the top of the food chain, they forage on the 
open ocean far from continental pollution sources, and we expected to find 
very low contaminant levels.  Our research demonstrates that global controls 
on the distribution of persistent, bioaccumulative toxic compounds need to be 
considered.  The problem can't be approached on a country-by-country basis."

<P>

So far, the researchers say, the effects of chemical contaminants are nowhere 
near as serious as the deaths of albatrosses in fishing nets.  Nearly 4,500 
albatrosses were killed in drift nets in 1990 alone.  Dr. Giesy noted, however, 
that concentrations of PCBs and dioxin-like chemicals in albatrosses were at a 
threshold where "a very small increment in the toxic dose can cause a steep 
response" in adverse population-level effects.

<P>

<I> Moose deaths linked to acid rain   </I>

<P>

A debilitating disease has killed more than 1,500 moose in the past decade in 
one county in Sweden.  Acid rain was the catalyst for the chain of events that 
led to the disease, say Swedish researchers.  The scientists believe the disease 
is caused by the spreading of lime to counteract the effects of acidification on 
the environment.  The lime appears to have caused a toxic imbalance in 
metal concentrations, specifically of the chemical elements copper and 
molybdenum, in the animals' livers.  This is "the first instance in which 
acidification has been linked to mortality in a warm-blooded wild animal," 
reports <I>The New York Times,  </I> 12 March 1996.

<P>

The practice of liming wetlands, lakes, fields, pastures and to a lesser extent 
forest areas began early in the 1980s, and intensified in the second half of the 
decade when the disease began occurring in the moose.  And, because many 
of the plants moose usually eat, such as blueberry bushes, have been 
decimated by acid rain, the animals grazing habits changed.  "Moose 
frequently browse on cultivated pastures and fields of oat and rape, all of 
which are heavily limed by farmers," says Dr. Adrian Frank, a chemist at the 
Center for Metal Biology.  Changing the pH of the soil mobilizes certain 
metals and makes others less soluble.  In this case, excessive molybdenum in 
relation to the amount of copper in the ruminant's diet appears to be causing 
a fatal copper deficiency.

<P>

"The animals are emaciated, their hair is discolored, their immune systems 
are impaired, and they suffer from osteoporosis, ulcers, diarrhea, 
convulsions, blindness and sudden heart failure," the article reports.  In a 
paper to be published by the American Chemical Society, Dr. Frank calls 
moose "a useful, fast and sensitive monitor of environmental change."  
Because they are found in northern areas around the world and eat a great 
variety of plants, they can provide information about changes in levels of 
metals within five years.

</BODY>
</HTML>
