<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Earth Pulse News Spring 1996 -  An update on the stratospheric 
ozone layer    </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H2>  An update on the stratospheric ozone layer    </H2>
</CENTER>

There is both good and bad news about the international effort to restrict the 
use of ozone-depleting chemicals and begin the process of restoring the 
protective strength of the stratospheric ozone layer.  Good news comes from 
atmospheric chemist Stephen Montzka of NOAA in Boulder, Colorado.  He 
reports that chlorine levels peaked at the end of 1994, at least in the lower 
atmosphere where they can be readily monitored.  Charles Jackman of 
Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Maryland reports that according to 
a computer model, ozone concentrations should begin recovering by the year 
2000 and return to 1979 levels (the year the Antarctic ozone hole became 
obvious) by around 2050, if chlorine controls hold.

<P>

The bad news, is that according to Ronald Prinn of MIT, gaps in the Montreal 
Protocol could slow this recovery.  While chlorine has peaked, bromine 
concentrations are still growing, and bromine is at least 40 times as potent an 
ozone-destroyer as chlorine, on an atom-for-atom basis.  The bromine comes 
primarily from halons in existing fire-protection systems and from methyl 
bromide, a soil and stored-grain fumigant.  While these chemicals are slated 
to be phased out, there are unspecified exemptions that may leave significant 
loopholes.  Even the threat of chlorine from CFCs is far from eliminated.  
While developed countries have largely made the shift away from these 
chemicals, one substitute, the HCFCs,  are weak ozone depleters, and are still 
contributing to chlorine levels.  In addition, most developing countries, 
which have laxer timetables for CFC phase-out, have been slow to implement 
the switch.  Though much has been accomplished, the Montreal Protocol's 
work is clearly not finished.

<P>

<H3> Classroom Connection:  Acting out the drama of ozone depletion 
</H3>

<P>

The key chemical reaction that destroys ozone (O3) molecules is initiated by 
UV radiation from the sun, which breaks up CFC and other chlorine-
containing molecules to free chlorine monoxide atoms.  These highly 
reactive chlorine atoms (Cl) capture one of the oxygen atoms (O) from an 
ozone molecule, forming a new chlorine-oxygen molecule and an oxygen 
molecule (O2).  (Cl + O3 becomes ClO + O2).  This chlorine-oxygen molecule 
then reacts with an oxygen atom, which frees the chlorine atom again.  When 
it finds another ozone molecule, the destruction occurs again and again and 
again.

<P>

Students can make and put on hats (or other costumes) that identify them as 
Cl or O atoms and hold hands to form molecules.  The students that are 
chlorine molecules "break into" the groups that are ozone molecules (O3) and 
convert them into ClO and O2.  This experiment helps students see how the 
ozone-destruction process occurs again and again.

<P>

A great deal of information on stratospheric ozone can be found at the TOMS 
(Total Ozone Mapping Spectrometer) Home Page at <A 
HREF="http://jwocky.gsfc.nasa.gov/"> http://jwocky.gsfc.nasa.gov/</A>    
or go straight to the "Ozone Info" part of their page at <A 
HREF="http://jwocky.gsfc.nasa.gov/basics/basics.html"> 
http://jwocky.gsfc.nasa.gov/basics/basics.html</A> where you can find 
information describing the TOMS instrument, how ozone is measured, facts 
about ozone depletion, a glossary of terms, and how to obtain TOMS ozone 
data on-line and on CD ROM.  Links to various educational resources and 
activities can also be found at this site.

</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
