<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>  Earth Pulse News Spring 1996 - Responses of fish populations to 
human influences  </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H2>  Responses of fish populations to human influences   </H2>
</CENTER>

<P>
Researchers have found that in a number of overexploited fish species, 
including haddock, cod and flounder, females have begun to spawn at an 
earlier age.  While rebuilding stocks rapidly, this response poses a different set 
of risks to the population, reports an article in the December 1995 issue of 
<I>BioScience.</I>  Prior to the recent collapse of cod fisheries off the coast of 
Canada, annual harvests often removed 60% of the older adults (three times 
the recommended amount to sustain healthy stocks).  As a result, in some 
cod stocks the age of first spawning has been nearly halved, from 5 or 6 years 
to less than 3.  The researchers even cite an unpublished finding that Georges 
Banks cod spawn at 1.87 years old.  The younger mothers, which make up an 
increasingly large proportion of stressed stocks, weigh less and produce fewer 
and smaller eggs which yield smaller, weaker, less active young which are 
more vulnerable to predation.  The volume of a cod's eggs drops by about 
38% as the mother's length falls from 25.5 inches to 19.  While a 34-inch long 
mother produces about 3.2 million eggs, a 17-inch spawner releases just 
370,000, the researchers report.


</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B15-147</DOCNO>
