<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>    Earth Pulse News Spring 1996 - New research documents 
amphibian decline  </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<CENTER>
<H2>   New research documents amphibian decline    </H2>
</CENTER>

<I>The New York Times,</I> 30 April 1996, reporting on a new study 
published in <I>Conservation Biology,</I> discusses what researchers say is 
"the first documentation of a large-scale collapse of an entire community of 
frog species."  Biologists have found that all seven native species of frogs and 
toads in the Yosemite region have declined since early in the century, and 
three of these species have disappeared from this largely pristine wilderness 
in and around Yosemite National Park.

<P>

The new study compared results from a 1915 survey with those of a recent 
survey, providing much-needed long-term data.  The results indicate that the 
declines in amphibian populations noted by many researchers are not likely 
to be explained by harmless, short term fluctuations.  The researchers also 
ruled out habitat destruction as the cause of the decline observed in this 
study, noting that the site "is about as pristine an area as you can find in the 
lower 48 United States."  Drought was also ruled out as a cause since both the 
1915 and the recent survey were conducted after similar lengthy dry periods.

<P>

Introduced fish seem to be a leading contender in the search for causes of the 
decline, as stocked trout eat eggs, tadpoles and adult frogs.  Other causes are 
hypothesized to include chemical pollution (including acidification), disease, 
increased ultraviolet light (due to the thinning ozone layer), and interactions 
between these causes.  Researchers say continued monitoring is needed to pin 
down the causes but funding for the Declining Amphibian Populations Task 
Force is insecure.

<P>

<H3>Classroom Connection: </H3>

Students can access the Declining Amphibian Populations Task Force Home 
Page at <A 
HREF="http://www.open.ac.uk/OU/Academic/Biology/J_Baker/JBtxt.htm"
>http://www.open.ac.uk/OU/Academic/Biology/J_Baker/JBtxt.htm</A> as 
well as a link from this site to <I>Froglog,</I> the quarterly newsletter of the 
Task Force.  See <I>EarthPulse NEWS,</I> <A 
HREF="../EPNews.html#link">Winter 1996</A>, for 
information on how to get involved in an amphibian monitoring program.


</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
