<html><head><title>Earth Pulse News Winter 1996 - Where Have all 
the Frogs Gone?</title></head>
<body>

<h2><p align=center>Where Have All the Frogs Gone?</h2>

Amphibian populations are in serious decline in many areas of the 
world and scientists are seeking explanations for this disturbing 
phenomenon.  "The Puzzle of Declining Amphibian Populations," by 
Andrew R. Blaustein and David B. Wake, in <i>Scientific American</i>, 
April 1995, pp. 52-57 reviews the various factors contributing to 
these losses.  As is the case with most threatened species, destruction 
and modification of habitats like forests and wetlands are probably 
the most serious causes of the decline, according to the authors.  
Another major reason for the decline of certain species is the fact 
that increased levels of ultraviolet-B (UV-B) radiation from the sun 
damages the DNA of some species in the egg stage.  An enzyme called 
photolyase protects the eggs of certain species from destructive UV-
B.  In species which produce little photolyase, research has 
demonstrated that UV-B destroys large numbers of eggs, resulting in 
falling populations.

<p>It is speculated that the mechanism by which the UV-B destroys 
the eggs and embryos is that it impairs immune function, allowing 
diseases, such as the fungus-like organism <i>Saprolegnia</i>, to infect 
the eggs.  Research has shown that <i>Saprolegnia </i>can also destroy 
whole populations of tadpoles.  Aside from harming eggs, UV-B may 
contribute to the decline in amphibian populations by reducing the 
supply of aquatic insects by killing insect larvae on which they feed.  
In addition, evidence suggests that acid rain, fungicides, herbicides, 
insecticides, and some industrial chemicals may impair the 
reproduction and development of amphibians.  Collection of frogs for 
human consumption also takes a toll; in France, 80 million frogs a 
year are killed for frog legs.  Introduced species of non-native fish 
and bullfrogs also contribute to the decline by preying on native 
amphibian populations, outcompeting them for food and other 
resources, and/or introducing exotic diseases.

<h3>Classroom Connection:</h3>
You can get involved in an exciting program in which students 
monitor local amphibian populations and communicate about their 
results with other students and scientists around the world.  To learn 
more about this project, contact Karen Toepfer, Amphibians as Bio-
Indicators, e-mail:  <a 
href="mailto:fmkt@fhsuvm.fhsu.edu">fmkt@fhsuvm.fhsu.edu</a>, 
phone:  913-628-1437, or mail:  303 W. 39th Street, Hays, Kansas  
67601.  Also, be sure to visit the World Wide Web page of the World 
Conservation Union Species Survival Commission's <a 
href="http://www.open.ac.uk/OU/Academic/Biology/J_Baker/JBtxt.htm">Declining Amphibians Task Force</a>.  There you will find a 
quarterly publication called <em>FrogLog </em> as well as links to 
other information about amphibians and how their populations are 
changing.
</body>
</html>

