<html><head><title>EarthPulse News Winter 1996 - Interactive Effects 
of Ground-Level Ozone and Climate Warming on Trees</title></head
<body>
<h2><p align=center>Interactive Effects of Ground-Level Ozone 
and Climate Warming on Trees</h2>

The study of global change often involves examining the 
"synergisms" or interactions between multiple environmental 
changes; this story deals with one such synergism.  New research 
indicates that increasing exposure to <a 
href="glossary2.html#tropo">tropospheric</a> or ground-level ozone 
(a pollutant that results from the interaction of sunlight with 
emissions from automobiles and industry), particularly when 
combined with higher air temperatures and lower soil moisture, 
reduces growth in mature loblolly pine trees.  These trees occupy 25 
million hectares and contribute over $4.5 billion to the economy of 
the southeastern US.  During the mid-1980s, unexplained declines in 
growth in these pine stands was detected, and tropospheric ozone 
was suggested as a possible cause.

<p>The research described in <em>Nature</em>, Vol. 374 No. 6519, 16 
March 1995, "Interactive effects of ambient ozone and climate 
measured on growth of mature forest trees," by S. B. McLaughlin and 
D. L. Downing, was a five-year study of changes in stem 
circumference of 28 mature loblolly pines.  The study has roughly 
defined the threshold of ozone levels at which the trees respond and 
quantified short- and longer-term components of growth responses 
to varying ozone and climate variables.  The researchers report that 
the variability in seasonal growth is closely associated with 
fluctuations in ozone exposure and that interactions between ozone 
exposure and soil moisture stress exacerbated the declines.  The 
authors conclude that the sensitivity of the ozone effects to moisture 
and temperature "may become particularly significant if the climate 
changes predicted by global climate models are realized.  Predictions 
of increases in ozone by 2025 in the large urban-agricultural areas of 
the world further emphasize the potential hazards that these effects 
pose."
</body>
</html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B15-151</DOCNO>
