<html><head><title>EarthPulse News Winter 1996 - The International 
Climate Change Convention</title></head>
<body>
<h2><p align=center>The International Climate Change 
Convention</h2>

As scientists collect new data and work to improve their models of 
how future climate might respond to increasing human-caused 
emissions of greenhouse gases, politicians around the globe are 
grappling with how to reduce those emissions and thus prevent the 
worst scenarios from coming true.  "Keeping the <a 
href="glossary2.html#treaty">Climate Treaty</a> Relevant," by David 
Victor and Julian Salt, in <em>Nature</em>, Vol. 373 No. 6512, 26 
January 1995, pp. 280-282, makes the argument that contrary to 
conventional wisdom, forcing compliance with strict limits on 
emissions is not the best way to approach this problem.  Binding 
targets and timetables for greenhouse gas (GHG) emission reductions 
should wait, these authors say, because they are not as important as 
getting better information on actual emissions and reviewing the 
performance of nations.  Also, when negotiating binding agreements, 
nations engage in tortuous legal drafting which could result in "hard" 
law with "soft" language, which would be ineffective.

<p>To manage climate policies, the authors say, three classes of 
information are needed: accurate, comparable and disaggregated 
(broken down by gas and source) emissions of GHGs; planned policies 
and measures with forecasts of their effects on emissions; and 
standards against which to judge these actions.  What will make 
these sources of information truly useful is periodic and systematic 
review and assessment.  The authors recommendations include the 
following:  1) don't focus on tough targets and timetables;  2) give the 
process of gathering and reviewing information the political space to 
operate;  3) increase the use of comparable national reports;  4) 
support the Climate Convention's secretariat with funding and staff; 
and  5) design an effective process to review implementation 
questions.  An interesting note:  A team of experts has found that of 
the 15 nations reporting thus far, 5 will meet their targets, 5 will 
miss them, and 5 are uncertain.

<p>In other news relevant to the Climate Convention, in <em>New 
Scientist</em>, 1 April 1995, p. 5, Fred Pearce reports on economists' 
efforts to place a dollar value on human lives.  "Price of life sends 
temperatures soaring," discusses a draft of a forthcoming report from 
the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) dealing with 
the economics of climate change.  This report values a dead American 
at $1.5 million, but a dead citizen of a "low-income country" at one-
tenth as much, or $150,000.  India's environment minister called the 
calculation "absurd and discriminatory" while proponents explain 
that it is simply based on average earnings.  Later articles say that 
the report's authors have not backed down from their assertions that 
the calculations are appropriate for measuring the potential economic 
effects of climate change.

<p>Such economic calculations are important because, with global 
warming projected to be responsible for the deaths of more than 
200,000 people a year within 50 years, the value placed on a human 
life largely determines the "cost" of climate change.  It also 
determines what measures are cost-effective to mitigate warming.  
Sam Fankhauser, the economist behind the controversial figures, 
calculates that there will be five times as many deaths in poor 
countries as in the Organization for Economic Cooperation and 
Development (OECD) nations as a result of warming, but that the cost 
of the OECD mortality is more than twice as great.  He argues that the 
calculation is an economic device and "does not mean that the life of 
a Chinese is worth less than that of an European Community citizen," 
but critics don't feel this explanation is sufficient.  The calculations 
are still causing a heated debate.

An interdisciplinary meeting, "Improving the Effectiveness of the 
Climate Change Convention," was held at the Aspen Global Change 
Institute in August 1995.  The full report of this meeting will soon be 
available on the <a href="/../agci-home.html">AGCI homepage</a>.  
Many of the issues raised above were discussed at the meeting and 
are featured in the report.

<h3>Classroom Connection:</h3>
Students can negotiate their own climate convention by playing the 
roles of delegates from various countries.  Among the many 
questions they might seek to address are: How do the concerns of 
developed nations differ from those of less developed countries?  
What kinds of provisions do the various delegates want included in 
the treaty?  What leverage do the various parties have?  Some 
students can represent the working groups of the Intergovernmental 
Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), the scientific body that provides 
information to delegates to the convention.  There is a good resource 
for students on the World Wide Web called <a 
href="http://www.unep.ch/iucc/begincon.html"> "Understanding 
Climate Change: A Beginner's Guide to the UN Framework 
Convention"</a>.  
For additional technical detail, see the <a 
href="http://www.unep.ch/ipcc/ipcc-0.html">IPCC homepage</a>.  
Students can also search the Web for information on their various 
roles in the negotiation process.  For access to many referenes 
relevant to the IPCC, students can search AGCI's <a href="/../ASPEN/epnotes/epnotes.html">EarthPulse 
Notes</a>.
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
