<html><head><title>EarthPulse News Winter 1996 - Salps May Provide 
a Negative Climate Feedback</title></head>
<body>

<h2><p align=center>Salps May Provide a Negative Climate 
Feedback</h2>

Recent reports from marine biologists discussed in <em>Scientific 
American</em>, December 1995, pp. 28-29, suggest that tiny, 
gelatinous, tubelike animals called <a href="Salps.gif">salps</a> may be responsible for a 
portion of the <a href="glossary2.html#missing">missing carbon 
sink</a>.  The Southern Ocean's temperature has increased an 
average of 2 to 2.5 degrees C during the last 40 years, and salps, 
which thrive in warmer waters, have blossomed, replacing krill as 
the dominant form of <a 
href="glossary2.html#zooplankton">zooplankton</a> in the area.  
There was a fourfold increase in salp biomass between 1980 and 
1990, according to data from Soviet researchers, and the salps have 
continued to spread much further south than before.

<p>Salps are important for what they eat and excrete.  Salps rise to 
the surface to graze during the day on phytoplankton (tiny plants 
that draw carbon dioxide from the air in the process of 
photosynthesis).  At night, salps return to the depths as much as a 
kilometer below and there they dump carbon-rich fecal pellets that 
sink as fast as 2.7 kilometers per day.  So where there are salps, the 
efficiency of carbon transfer from the atmosphere to deep sea 
sediments (the "biological pump") is improved dramatically.  Once 
buried in sea sediments, the carbon is out of the system for 
thousands of years.  Because salps seem to proliferate as water 
temperatures rise, biologists think they may provide a negative <a 
href="glossary2.html#feedback">feedback</a> to climate warming: 
theoretically, more CO<sub>2</sub> leads to more warming, more 
salps, and more efficient carbon transfer, which eventually leads to 
less CO<sub>2</sub> and less warming.

<p>Reality may be a good deal more complicated than this, however, 
the researchers say.  For one thing, there may not be enough salps to 
make much of difference in terms of large scale climatic effects.  For 
another, too much of a good thing can be lethal to salps.  When the 
phytoplankton get too dense, a condition that might be more 
frequent as CO<sub>2</sub> levels rise, the salps' digestive systems 
become clogged.  Salps literally starve to death because they are in 
the midst of plenty.  It will take much more research to determine 
how this ecosystem will respond to and affect rising CO<sub>2</sub> 
levels and water temperature and how much of an effect can be 
expected.  Stay tuned for new developments.
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
<DOC>
