<html><head><title>EarthPulse News Winter 1996 - The Decline of the 
World's Fisheries 
and the Treaty Designed to Save Them</title></head>
<body>

<h2><p align=center>The Decline of the World's Fisheries 
and the Treaty Designed to Save Them</h2>

The National Marine Fisheries Service estimates that 45% of the fish 
stocks whose status is known are now overfished, and populations of 
some species have fallen to less than 10% of the "optimum level" (the 
level that yields the largest sustainable catch).  In "Biologists Sort the 
Lessons of Fisheries Collapse," <em>Science</em>, Vol. 264 No. 5163, 
27 May 1994, pp. 1252-3, Bob Holmes reports on how signs of 
trouble in fish populations were ignored and led to the collapse of 
many of the world's important fisheries.  This article expresses the 
view of fisheries scientists that their advice and information has not 
been headed by the fisheries councils that are responsible for setting 
fishing limits.  Among the worst offenders, they say, is the New 
England Fishing Council, which even now, in the face of fisheries 
collapse, allows fishermen there to catch 60% of the entire fish 
population each year  more than twice the sustainable level.  

<p>"How could an advanced nation with an army of scientists allow 
one of the richest fisheries in the world to be destroyed?" asks an 
article in <em>New Scientist</em>, Vol. 147 No. 1995, 16 September 
1995, pp. 24-29.  The destruction of Canada's Grand Banks cod 
fishery fell prey to the usual list of suspects, the author says, 
including a government setting fishing limits higher than scientists 
advised and fishermen who cheated on catch quotas.  But the models 
used to estimate sustainable catches are also implicated; according to 
these models, the Grand Banks should still be full of fish.  Meanwhile, 
these same models are being used to govern other fisheries around 
the world.  It is now realized that Canada's biologists relied too much 
on data from commercial catches to estimate the sizes of fish stocks.  
They also based their assessments of safe catches on flawed 
assumptions about fish biology.  So overfishing may continue even if 
scientific advice is heeded because the advise may be wrong.  And 
once depleted, a fishery may never recover.  On the Great Banks, the 
haddock population was wiped out in the 1950s and never recovered 
and the yellowtail flounder may not come back.  One scientist says, 
"there is a strong inverse association between the growth of fisheries 
science...and the effectiveness with which it is applied."

<p>A United Nations conference on high seas fisheries has drafted a 
strong global treaty on the management and conservation of the 
world's vulnerable fish stocks, reports <em>New Scientist</em>, 5 
August 1995.  Once approved, the treaty must be ratified by 30 
countries before it will have the force of law, a process that could 
take many years.  Delegates say the treaty is the strongest statement 
to date of the precautionary approach in fisheries policy.  If 
estimates of fish numbers are uncertain, fisheries managers should 
assume the worst, not the best, and inadequate information should 
not be used as an excuse to postpone conservation efforts.

<p>The issue of enforcement was controversial among the delegates, 
particularly with regard to the right to board, inspect, and if 
necessary, seize foreign vessels believed to be fishing illegally.  
Another article in <em>New Scientist</em>, 12 August 1995, p. 7, 
reports that the draft was unanimously approved with the provision 
that allows boarding and inspection.  While many delegates are 
pleased with the protections offered by the new treaty, some, 
including the environmental group Greenpeace, say it is "too weak to 
save plummeting fish stocks" because it does not require nations to 
reduce the size of their fishing fleets or use environmentally safe 
fishing gear.

<h3>Classroom Connection:</h3>
Find out more about the condition of fisheries and other interesting 
information at the homepage on the <a 
href="http://www.netspace.org/MFCN/T13.html">National Agenda to 
Protect, Restore and Conserve Marine Fisheries</a>. 

<p>From the University of New Hampshire's Institute for Policy and 
Social Science Research comes an excellent game called "Fish Banks" 
which can help bring the issues involved in fisheries management 
home.  In this simulation, students act as managers of fishing 
companies who must collect and analyze data and make decisions to 
maximize their assets.  Higher- level thinking, cooperative learning 
and group problem solving are among the skills developed in this 
process.  A description of this game and information on how to order 
it can be found on the <a 
href="http://unhinfo.unh.edu:70/0/unh/institutes/ipssr/FishBank.html">Fish Banks homepage</a>, or by contacting Luisa Fowler, by 
email at <a href="mailto:lgf@christa.unh.edu">lgf@christa.unh.edu</a>, 
by mail at IPSSR-Hood House, University of New Hampshire, 89 Main 
Street, Durham, NH 03824-3577; by phone at (603) 862-2186, or by 
fax at (603) 862-1488.

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
