</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head><title>EPNEWS Fall 1995 - We've Looked at 
Clouds</title></head>
<body>
<h2><p align=center>We've Looked at Clouds From Both Sides 
Now</h2>

Clouds have an enormous effect on climate.  They cool the Earth by 
reflecting some of the sun's radiation away from Earth and back to 
space, but they also warm the planet by holding in some of the sun's 
energy re-radiated by Earth.  Some types of clouds are more 
reflective while others are more blanketing.  Researchers working on 
improving our understanding of the net effect of these competing 
mechanisms now believe that on average, clouds act to cool the Earth 
more than warm it.  If Earth had no clouds, the planet would be 
warmer than it is now.  One of the things scientists are currently 
studying is how clouds may change due to changes in the atmosphere 
caused by human beings.<p>

As human activities, notably the burning of <a 
href=EPglossary.html#fossilf>fossil fuels</a>, continue to increase, 
more heat-trapping gases (like carbon dioxide and methane), are 
released into the atmosphere, enhancing the <a 
href=EPglossary.html#geffect>greenhouse effect</a> and thus causing 
warming of Earth's atmosphere near the surface.  Clouds are one of 
the key mechanisms that may further enhance this warming or 
counteract it.  Until scientists learn more about how clouds may 
change as climate changes, we will not know what is in store for our 
climate future.   As policy-makers grapple with restricting emissions 
of greenhouse gases through an international <a 
href=EPglossary.html#ccconv>climate change convention</a>, 
scientists continue to study the physics and chemistry of cloud-
climate interactions to provide information needed in the policy 
arena.<p>

Such new information has come to light in recent months, as new 
data collected by observing the same clouds from Earth's surface and 
from satellites have created quite a stir among climate researchers.  
Two articles with enormous implications for our understanding of 
clouds and climate were published in the journal <em>Science</em>, 
Vol 267, 27 January 1995.  The subject of these articles, how much of 
the sun's energy is absorbed by clouds, is one of the cutting edge 
issues in current climate research.  "Absorption of Solar Radiation by 
Clouds: Observations Versus Models," by Cess <em>et al</em>., reports 
the results of observing the same clouds from above and below to 
assess how much <a href=EPglossary.html#swrad>shortwave solar 
radiation</a> is actually absorbed by clouds.  Co-located satellite and 
surface measurements of solar radiation at five geographically 
diverse locations showed that clouds actually absorb about 25 watts 
per square meter more radiation than predicted by theoretical 
models.  This could result in about 20% less solar energy reaching the 
ground than was previously believed.  "<a 
href=EPglossary.html#wpool>Warm Pool</a> Heat Budget and 
Shortwave Cloud Forcing: A Missing Physics?," by Ramanathan et al., 
and "Direct Observations of Excess Solar Absorption by Clouds," by 
Pilewskie and Valero, Science, Vol. 267, 17 March 1995, both report 
very similar findings based on data collected over the tropical 
western Pacific Ocean.<p>

The results reported in these articles could have dramatic 
implications for the <a href=EPglossary.html#gcms>general circulation 
models</a> used in climate research.  None of these models has 
accurately reproduced Earth's current climate as yet.  But when one 
of these supercomputer models (the National Center for Atmospheric 
Research's Community Climate Model 2) was recently altered to 
make its clouds absorb shortwave radiation in line with the new 
observations, the results were promising; it compared better with 
observations of the present climate than the previous version of the 
model.<p>

On the other hand, new research reported in the 10 August 1995 
issue of <em>Nature</em>, Vol. 376, reaches a different conclusion.  
In "The variable effect of clouds on atmospheric absorption of solar 
radiation," Zhanqing Li <em>et al</em>. find that the increased 
absorption occurs only in warm seasons - mainly in the tropics and 
mid-latitude summers.  At other times, they find a tendency toward 
greater absorption than predicted by current models, but far less 
than in the results of the articles discussed above.  Li <em>et al</em>. 
speculate that there is no mysterious absorber, but rather that the 
algorithms used to process satellite data may be wrong for highly 
heterogeneous cloud scenes (high variation of cloud types, sizes, 
and/or distributions).  Such scenes are more prevalent in warm 
seasons, precisely the seasons in which Li <em>et al</em>. find the 
greatest anomaly.  Climate researchers continue to work towards 
better comprehension of the physics of radiation absorption by 
clouds and will use this knowledge to improve the accuracy of the 
models that may offer us a window on future climate.<p>

As we learn more about the complexities of climate interactions, it is 
sobering to realize that, as Roger Revelle and Hans Suess wrote in 
1957, "human beings are now carrying out a large scale geophysical 
experiment of a kind which could not have happened in the past nor 
be reproduced in the future."  When those words were written, 38 
years ago, the carbon dioxide concentration of Earth's atmosphere 
had already risen from a pre-industrial level of about 280 parts per 
million to 315 parts per million.  The increase has continued and the 
level of CO2 is now nearly 360 parts per million in 1995.  The global 
experiment continues.<p>

<h3>Classroom Connection:  Clouds</h3>

Students can do an experiment to investigate how clouds reflect 
radiation and keep it from reaching the surface.  Students begin by 
measuring the temperature of sand in a sandbox (or tray) before the 
sun hits the surface and again every hour until noon.  They build a 
set of "clouds" out of materials with different transmissivities such as 
pieces of gauze, paper, screen door screening, plastic, wood, etc., and 
then hold each of these clouds over the sandbox for five minutes, 
taking the temperature of the sand after each trial.  They'll see a 
range from very little to dramatic change in the temperature of the 
sand at the surface as a result of their reflective clouds.<p>

To explore the blanketing part of the equation, on a clear night, 
students can measure the temperature of the sand in two different 
sandboxes or trays and then cover one of them with a blanket 
overnight.  First thing in the morning, students can measure the 
temperature of the sand in the two boxes and see if the blanket kept 
the sand warmer and if so, by how much.  The concept of the 
competing effects of cloud reflectivity and blanketing is one that 
students of all ages can grasp.  If you come up with additional 
activities for exploring this topic, please let us know.
</body></html>
</DOC>
