<html>
<head><title>EPNEWS Fall 1995 - Climatic Warming and the Decline of Zooplankton</title></head>
<body>

<h2><p align=center>
Climatic Warming and the Decline of Zooplankton in the California 
Current</h2>

Researchers who have spent 40 years measuring 
the presence of tiny 
animal organisms called <a 
href=EPglossary.html#zoop>zooplankton</a> living in California's 
coastal waters have discovered an alarming fact: Since 1951, the 
biomass (living weight) of zooplankton in the waters off the coast of 
southern California has decreased by 70%.  During that same period, 
the surface layer of the ocean warmed, by more than 1.5 degrees C in 
some places, and the temperature difference between the layers 
increased.  This increased stratification resulted in less lifting of 
deeper waters by wind-driven <a 
href=EPglossary.html#upwell>upwelling</a>.  A shallower source of 
upwelled waters provide less inorganic nutrients for new biological 
production and hence supported a smaller zooplankton population.  View a picture of plankton nets <a href=plankton.html>here</a>.<p>

The authors, Dean Roemmich and John McGowan, point out that if 
this trend is anthropogenic (human-caused) in origin, or is a long-
term natural trend, there is cause for great concern globally.  "The 
suppression of nutrient supply by enhanced stratification is not a 
mechanism confined to coastal oceans.  If there is a global 
temperature rise of 1 to 2 degrees C in the next 40 years and 
stratification increases globally, the biological impacts could be 
devastating.  Our study also demonstrates that climate studies 
dominated by short-term process-oriented experiments cannot 
simply be extrapolated to decadal time scales, where the balance of 
terms is different from monthly or seasonal balances," the authors 
say.  For further information, see their article in <em>Science</em>, 
Vol. 267, 3 March 1995, pp. 1324-1326.<p>

An article in <em>New Scientist</em>, Vol 146, 8 April 1995, p. 5, and 
another in <em>Science</em>, Vol. 267, 31 March 1995, p.1912-1913, 
discuss Roemmich and McGowan's research and point to other recent 
studies conducted in the region that reveal significant declines in 
numbers of birds and fish that feed on zooplankton, indicating that 
the effects of the plankton decline are already rippling up through 
the <a href=EPglossary.html#foodweb>food web</a>.  The <em>New 
Scientist </em> article further points out that the research reported 
here mirrors changes predicted by James Lovelock and Lee Krump 
who warned that warming would increase stratification, reduce 
growth of plankton, and thus reduce the amount of carbon dioxide 
absorbed by the oceans, introducing a positive climate <a 
href=EPglossary.html#fdback>feedback</a> by further amplifying 
increases in temperature.  Currently, 20 to 40% of the carbon dioxide 
added by humans to the atmosphere is believed to be absorbed in 
the oceans, most of it by plankton.
</body>
</html>

</DOC>
