<html>
<head><title>EPNEWS Fall 1995 - Major Ozone Thinning Found Over 
the Arctic</title></head>
<body>

<h2><p align=center>Major Ozone Thinning Found Over the Arctic</h2>

The <a href=EPglossary.html#ozoneh>ozone hole</a> over Antarctica 
has focused attention regarding ozone depletion on the South Pole.  
There, the combination of chlorine monoxide in the <a 
href=EPglossary.html#stratos>stratosphere</a>, a strong <a 
href=EPglossary.html#pvort>polar vortex</a>, and cold enough 
conditions for the formation of <a href=EPglossary.html#pstrat>polar 
stratospheric clouds</a> concentrate ozone loss and create the major 
seasonal depletion known as the ozone hole.  Some scientists have 
expressed concern that similar conditions over the North Pole could 
cause the formation of a "hole" there, while others have contended 
that those conditions could not be reproduced over the Arctic.  Now 
the first evidence of major ozone depletion over the Arctic is in.<p>

A joint European research project has detected a significant reduction 
in ozone levels over the Arctic.  Analysis of both ground- and air-
based observations by the Second European Stratospheric Arctic and 
Mid-Latitude Experiment (SESAME) over the Arctic polar vortex has 
revealed a reduction of up to 50% in ozone levels at altitudes 
between 16 and 18 kilometers.  "A large part of this difference is 
likely to be caused by the chemical destruction of ozone," the team 
said in a recently-released statement, "but further analysis is 
required to quantify and confirm this."  The researchers found ozone 
levels in parts of the polar vortex falling at about 0.7% per day.  
SESAME is a two-year experiment funded by the European Union to 
examine the causes of ozone depletion in the northern hemisphere.  
SESAME's measurement phase is now nearing completion and will be 
followed by a period of intensive analysis.<p>

The US National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration has also 
established a monitoring program for the Northern Hemisphere and 
issues a summary report based on their ground-based and satellite 
data each April.  The most recent report states that "ozone 
measurements during the winter of 1994-95 indicate that total 
column ozone was unusually low over regions of the Northern 
Hemisphere.  For middle and high latitudes, ozone values were 10 to 
20% lower than typical values observed during these months in 1979 
and the early 1980s.  Over some high latitude regions, such as 
Siberia, total ozone in 1994-95 had decreased by up to 35% from 
1979 values."  The report is available on the World Wide Web from a 
link to the <a 
href=http://www.epa.gov/docs/ozone/index.html>Environmental 
Protection Agency's ozone homepage</a>.<p>

<h3>Classroom Connection:  Ozone</h3>

In recent months, you may have noticed a new feature on your local 
television weather forecasts called the UV Index.  This index predicts 
the intensity of the sun's ultraviolet radiation for the next day in 
your area.  The connection between UV and ozone depletion is that 
the stratospheric ozone layer screens out much of the sun's UV 
radiation, protecting life on Earth from damaging rays.  As many of 
us know first-hand, too much UV can cause sunburns.  Long-term UV 
exposure can also cause skin cancer and cataracts.  As a result of 
anthropogenic emissions of <a href=EPglossary.html#cfcs>CFCs</a>, <a 
href=EPglossary.html#halon>halons</a> and other chemicals, there 
has been a reduction in the amount of ozone in the stratosphere and 
hence, more harmful UV radiation reaching the Earth.<p>

The UV Index indicates the amount of UV radiation reaching the 
Earth's surface over the one-hour period around noon.  It is 
expressed on a simple 0-10 scale, with 0 representing a minimal 
level of UV exposure and 10 indicating a very high level of exposure.  
When the sun is low in the sky or the conditions are overcast, lower 
numbers can be expected.  The Index is calculated on the basis of 
several factors: latitude, date (season), time of day, and total ozone in 
the atmosphere as measured by the National Oceanic and 
Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).  These data are plugged into a 
computer model to determine how much atmosphere the UV rays 
must pass through to reach the surface.  The greater the distance and 
more ozone the rays must pass through, the lower the UV at the 
surface.  The UV value from the model is then adjusted for the 
elevation and the predicted cloud conditions for each specific 
location.  Currently, the Index is calculated for 58 US cities.<p>

Students can keep track of the UV index for your area, plot the 
results on a graph and initiate research projects based on this data.  
They can compare their data with that of other regions and learn 
more about how and why UV levels vary over places and times.  One 
source of information is the US Environmental Protection Agency's 
Stratospheric Ozone Hotline at (800) 296-1996, from 10 am to 4 pm 
eastern time.  Another is <a 
href=http://www.epa.gov/docs/ozone/index.html>EPA's ozone 
homepage</a> on the World Wide Web which contains a great deal of 
accessible information about ozone science and policy as well as links 
to many other sources of data on the subject.  One of these links will 
take you to a an extensive FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions) on 
ozone; others will take you fact sheets on specific ozone issues and 
information on what individuals can do about ozone depletion.  This 
is an issue that affects all life on Earth and one that students can 
investigate in a variety of ways.<p>
</DOC>
