<html>
<head><title>EPNEWS Fall 1995 - Decline of Forest Birds Due to 
Cascading Acid Rain Effects</title></head>
<body>

<h2><p align=center>Decline of Forest Birds Due to Cascading Acid Rain 
Effects</h2>

An unexpected consequence of forest decline due to <a 
href=EPglossary.html#acidp>acid precipitation</a> was observed in 
the 1980s when some birds in heavily damaged forests in the 
Netherlands began producing eggs with thin, porous shells and 
decreased viability.  The nature of that link has now been discovered 
and is the subject of a research article entitled "Poor reproduction in 
forest passerines from decline of snail abundance on acidified soils," 
appearing in <em>Nature</em>, 31 March 1994, pp. 446-448.  A 
decrease in soil calcium due to acidification reduces the snail 
population in the forest and these snails are the birds' main source of 
calcium.  Similar laying deficiencies in birds are reported from other 
acidified regions elsewhere in Europe.  This is the first experimental 
evidence of calcium limitations in wild birds and reveals a previously 
overlooked consequence of acid deposition.  It is also an example of 
the cascading effects that can occur in ecosystems as a result of 
various environmental impacts.<p>

<h3>Classroom Connection:  Birds and acid rain</h3>

Students can set up a local "acid rain watch" program.  They can look 
for local data on the acidity of precipitation in your area, graph these 
data, and look for trends.  They might also collect rain samples and 
measure their pH, as well as measuring the pH of local rivers or 
lakes.  Broadening the study, students can identify several local bird 
species and find out if and when they migrate, what they eat, and 
what eats them.  They can then try to hypothesize what kinds of 
ecosystem effects might occur if any of these species were to 
disappear from the area.  What value do species of birds have to 
you?  To other organisms in the ecosystem?  Have a wildlife expert 
visit your classroom and help provide information on various birds' 
roles in the local environment.  Use a field guide such as the 
Audubon Society Pocket Guide: Familiar Birds of North America 
(Alfred Knopf, New York) to help in identification.


</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT24-B15-158</DOCNO>
