<html>
<head><title>EPNEWS Fall 1995 - Coral Bleaching and Ocean 
Warming</title></head>
<body>

<h2><p align=center>Coral Bleaching and Ocean Warming</h2>

"<a href=EPglossary.html#coral>Coral</a> bleaching" is raising 
concerns about conditions in the oceans and possible implications for 
a variety of life forms.  Coral bleaching occurs as coral tissue expels a 
type of <a href=EPglossary.html#algae>algae</a> that resides in its 
structure and is necessary to its survival.  The algae, called 
zooxanthellae, in addition to giving color to the otherwise white coral 
skeleton, produce carbon compounds that nourish the coral.  In 
return, the coral provides the algae with a home and with nitrogen 
and phosphorous, which are essential for its survival.  This delicate 
symbiosis can be disturbed by a number of factors that may cause 
the coral to expel the algae.  Disturbances such as temperature 
extremes, hypersalinity, pollutants in the water, or changes in 
radiation flux can cause the coral to expel the algae and thus turn 
white and die.<p>

The correlation between warming ocean water temperatures and 
coral bleaching is of acute concern.  In the 1980s, many reefs showed 
signs of bleaching.  The most notable such events seemed to correlate 
with <a href=EPglossary.html#enino>El Ni&#241 o</a> events, which, 
among other things, cause a warming of surface waters in the 
equatorial Pacific Ocean.  Water temperatures of 30 degrees C at the 
peak of bleaching have raised concerns about a possible link between 
global warming and coral bleaching.  The 1982-83 strong 
El Ni&#241 o event, which resulted in sea surface temperature 
warming of 3-4 degrees C over the seasonal average, coincided with 
widespread, permanent coral bleaching across the equatorial eastern 
Pacific from Panama to Japan.  Recent studies seem to confirm that 
these bleaching episodes were caused by the elevated water 
temperatures.  Studies continue into the causes of other incidents of 
coral bleaching and possible wider implications.<p>

The first global study of coral bleaching suggests that major 
outbreaks of the phenomenon in the past decade were almost always 
caused by unusually high sea temperatures, probably linked to 
global warming.  (The algae provide both color and carbon to coral.  
Bleached coral often recovers in the next cool season, but if all the 
algae are lost, the coral will die.)  Thomas Goreau, a leading coral reef 
researcher, warns that global warming will increase the bleaching of 
coral and could seriously damage marine biodiversity.  He and 
colleague Raymond Hayes discerned a rising tide of coral bleaching 
from 1983 to 1991.  They compared its incidence with satellite data 
on average ocean temperatures.  They found that bleaching occurs in 
all waters and that the effect is not triggered by a specific 
temperature but by anomalous (unusual) warming locally.  The 
threshold appears to be a monthly mean water temperature more 
than 1 degree C higher than the long-term average.  According to the 
researchers, "Above that temperature, bleaching always took place, 
and below it, it did not."<p>

Most bleaching in the Pacific occurred in 1983, 87, and 91, when El 
Ni&#241 o caused warmer waters in the Tropical Pacific.  But , the 
researchers say, El Ni&#241 o is unlikely to have caused the 
bleaching in the Caribbean, where, they say, a strong warming trend 
persisted throughout the 1980s.  They point out that bleaching 
stopped abruptly in 1992, probably because of the cooling effect of 
the eruption of Mt. Pinatubo.  Goreau and Hayes call bleaching a 
"harbinger of reef ecosystem stress from ocean warming," and warn 
that it could "seriously impact marine biodiversity, fisheries, tourism, 
shore protection, and the ability to adapt to rising sea levels in over 
100 countries."

<h3>Classroom Connection:  Coral bleaching</h3>

Students can begin by researching the key locations of coral reefs 
globally and plotting these on a world map.  They can investigate the 
causes of coral bleaching as well as where and when these episodes 
have taken place.  They can plot the locations of these events on the 
map and keep track of new ones they learn about.  In addition to 
being a good exercise in geography, this may lead students to 
discover trends in coral bleaching events and links to global changes 
such as warming SSTs.
</body>
</html>

</DOC>
