<html><head><title>EPNEWS Fall 1995 - Glossary</title></head>
<body>

<h3>Terms from "Advances in Understanding Solar Energy 
Absorption by Clouds"</h3>

<strong><a name=fossilf>Fossil Fuels</a></strong> such as coal, oil, and 
natural gas are created by the decomposition of ancient animal and 
plant remains.  They are finite (limited) resources, and release 
carbon dioxide and other gases when burned.<p>

<strong><a name=geffect>Greenhouse Effect</a></strong> is the natural 
process whereby certain gases in Earth's atmosphere (such as water 
vapor, carbon dioxide, methane, and nitrous oxide) allow the Sun's 
energy in, but keep some of the energy that is re-radiated by the 
Earth from going back out.  Were it not for this natural effect, Earth's 
climate would be about 33 &#176 C (60&#176 F) colder, and life as 
we know it would not exist.  The "enhanced greenhouse effect" refers 
to increased levels of greenhouse gases from anthropogenic sources 
which may lead to warming of the Earth's climate.<p>

<strong><a name=ccconv>Climate Change Convention</a></strong> 
refers to the Framework Convention on Climate Change being 
negotiated under the auspices of the United Nations.  Currently, the 
agreement calls for developed nations who are parties to the treaty 
to seek to reduce their emissions of greenhouse gases to 1990 levels 
by the year 2000.  There are no sanctions for failing to meet this goal 
and there are no limitations on greenhouse gas emissions by 
developing countries at this time.  The Aspen Global Change Institute 
devoted one of its 1995 summer science sessions to the theme of 
"Improving the Effectiveness of the Climate Change Convention."  The 
report from this meeting will be available on-line by December 
1995.<p>

<strong><a name=swrad>Shortwave solar radiation</a></strong> refers 
to energy from the sun; its short wavelengths are associated with the 
high temperature body from which it emanates (the surface of the 
Sun is about 6000 &#176 Kelvin).  By contrast, the solar energy 
which is absorbed and re-radiated by the Earth is long wavelength 
because it emanates from the much cooler Earth (about 300 
&#176 K).  Earth's atmosphere is fairly transparent to this shortwave 
radiation, only absorbing about 15% of it, chiefly by water vapor.  
New research discussed in this issue of <em>EarthPulse NEWS </em> 
suggests that higher amounts of shortwave radiation may be 
absorbed by clouds than previously thought.  This issue is under 
continuing investigation.<p>

<strong><a name=wpool>Warm Pool</a></strong> refers to an area of 
the western Pacific Ocean which extends roughly between 140 
&#176 E to 170 &#176 E and 10 &#176 N to 10 &#176 S.  The 
annual mean sea surface temperature (SST) in this region attains the 
maximum value, about 302.5 &#176 Kelvin, observed for the world's 
oceans.  The warm pool atmosphere is humid and cloudy.  SSTs in 
this area are believed to be remarkably stable on geologic time 
scales.  For all of these reasons, it is an area of interest to researchers 
studying the interrelationships between SSTs, clouds and climate.<p>

<strong><a name=gcms>General Circulation Models</a></strong> 
(GCMs) are computer models of Earth's climate that are used to 
improve our understanding of factors that influence climate and 
enhance our ability to forecast future climate patterns.  One reason 
GCMs are so useful is that they allow researchers to turn individual 
variables on and off and observe the results, isolating factors in a 
way that is not possible in the physical world.<p>

<h3>Terms from "Climatic Warming and the Decline of Zooplankton in 
the California Current"</h3>

<strong><a name=zoop>Zooplankton</a></strong> are those plankton 
that are animals, as compared to phytoplankton, which are plants.  
Plankton are the small organisms that float or drift in water, 
especially at or near the surface.  Plankton include small crustaceans, 
algae, and protozoans, and serve as an important source of food for 
larger animals, such as fish.<p>

<strong><a name=upwell>Upwelling</a></strong> refers to the process, 
common along continental coastlines, in which nutrient-laden waters 
from the ocean depths rise to the surface.  Upwelling typically occurs 
when prevailing winds force warm surface waters away from the 
coast.  Cold, deep water then rises, or upwells, to replace the wind-
displaced surface water, bringing with it rich supplies of nutrients 
and causing an increase in the production of living organisms.<p>

<strong><a name=foodweb>Food Web</a></strong> refers to a group of 
interrelated food chains in a particular community.  A food chain is a 
group of organisms interrelated by the fact that each member of the 
group feeds upon on the one below it and is in turn eaten by the 
organism above it in the chain.<p>

<strong><a name=fdback>Feedback</a></strong> refers to a sequence 
of interactions in which the final interaction influences the original 
one.  In such a sequence, a cause produces a result, and the result 
then in turn influences its cause.  For example, by one estimate, 
global warming is expected to increase air conditioner use in the U.S. 
enough to require 86 additional power plants by the year 2010.  The 
burning of fossil fuels in those power plants would in turn cause 
more global warming, causing more air conditioner use, causing more 
warming, and so on, in a positive feedback loop.  As a system 
changes, it may generate processes that affect the original change.  If 
one of these processes amplifies the change (such as increasing global 
warming in the above example) we call it a positive feedback.  If it 
dampens the change, we call it a negative feedback.  Another, more 
personal example of a feedback is this: by sweating when doing 
work, our bodies maintain a temperature around 98.6 &#176 F; this 
is a negative feedback.<p>

<h3>Terms from "Major Ozone Hole Thinning Found Over the 
Arctic"</h3>

<strong><a name=ozoneh>Ozone Hole<ozoneh></strong> refers to a 
region of the atmosphere over Antarctica where, during springtime 
in the Southern Hemisphere, up to three quarters of the stratospheric 
ozone is destroyed.  Anthropogenic chemicals such as CFCs and 
Halons are the primary sources of the chlorine and bromine 
responsible for ozone loss.<p>

<strong><a name=stratos>Stratosphere</a></strong> is the region of 
the atmosphere between the troposphere and mesosphere, having a 
lower boundary approximately 8 kilometers above Earth's surface at 
the poles and 15 km at the equator and an upper boundary of 
approximately 50 km.  This is the region that houses the 
stratospheric ozone layer which protects Earth from ultraviolet solar 
radiation.<p>

<strong><a name=pvort>Polar Vortex</a></strong> refers to a strong, 
seasonal swirl of winds that occurs over the South Pole, isolating the 
stratosphere of that region during local Spring time (Austral or 
Southern Spring), and contributing to the conditions that cause the 
ozone hole.<p>

<strong><a name=pstrat>Polar Stratospheric Clouds</a></strong> are a 
special type of cloud that forms only under very cold conditions, 
lower than -78 &#176 C.  These clouds enhance the production and 
lifetime of reactive chlorine (from CFCs), leading to ozone 
depletion.<p>

<strong><a name=cfcs>CFCs</a></strong> are chlorine-containing 
chemicals which are use primarily as coolants in refrigerators, 
freezers, and air conditioners.  CFCs are also used as solvents, foam 
blowing agents and propellants, though the use of CFCs in aerosol 
cans in the U.S. was outlawed 15 years ago.  Though inert in the 
lower atmosphere, CFCs rise to stratosphere where their chlorine is 
freed and leads to ozone depletion.  Under the Montreal Protocol for 
the Protection of the Ozone Layer, the manufacture and use of CFCs is 
being phased out.  In the US and other industrialized countries, CFCs 
will no longer be manufactured after December 1995.  Though the 
amount of CFCs released to the atmosphere is decreasing, the 
concentrations of chlorine in the stratosphere are still very high and 
due to the long atmospheric lifetimes of CFCs, ozone destruction will 
continue to increase for many years.<p>

<strong><a name=halon>Halons</a></strong> are used primarily in fire 
extinguishers.  They contain bromine, a substance even more 
destructive to ozone than chlorine.  While the total amount of halons 
produced is far smaller than the amount of CFCs, molecule for 
molecule, halons are much more ozone-destructive, and so are also a 
serious concern.<p>

<h3>Terms from "Decline of Forest Birds Due to Cascading Acid Rain 
Effects</h3>

<strong><a name=acidp>Acid Precipitation</a></strong> is rain, snow, 
and other forms of precipitation made acidic by the addition of sulfur 
dioxide and nitrogen oxides into the atmosphere as a result of fossil 
fuel burning.  Automobile exhaust and emissions from coal-fired 
power plants are two significant causes of acid deposition.  In severe 
cases, acid precipitation kills fish and other aquatic life and damages 
trees and crops.  In some instances, it has rendered entire lakes and 
forests nearly lifeless.<p>

<h3>Terms from "Coral Bleaching and Ocean Warming"</h3>

<strong><a name=coral>Coral</a></strong> is a living skeleton 
consisting mainly of calcium carbonate usually formed by combined 
secretions of several species of carbonate-precipitating organisms.  
Near the surface of warm, shallow seas it can exist in the form of 
coral reefs or ridges.  Below a depth of 60 meters, corals are 
incapable of reef formation because the shortage of light limits 
photosynthesis by the algae that live in symbiosis with them.  Corals 
that lack algae can live down to a depth of about 80 meters.<p>

<strong><a name=algae>Algae</a></strong> are any of a large family of 
mostly aquatic organisms that contain chlorophyll.  Some algae are 
single-celled while others, such as certain seaweeds, are multicellular 
and may be very large.  Some live in symbiotic association with other 
organisms, such as algae and fungi in the form of lichens, or the algae 
and coral discussed in this <em>EarthPulse NEWS </em> article.<p>

<strong><enino>El Ni&#241 o</a></strong> is a warming of the surface 
waters of the eastern equatorial Pacific that occurs at irregular 
intervals of approximately 2 to 7 years, usually lasting 1 to 2 years, 
which has a significant influence on regional and global climate.  El 
Ni&#241 o has been linked to colder, wetter winters in parts of the 
U.S., drier hotter summers in South America and Europe, and drought 
in Africa, as well as reduced numbers of fish in South American 
coastal waters.
</body></html>

</DOC>
