<html>
<head><title>About the U.S. Country Studies Program</title>
</head>
<body>
<H2><A NAME="ap">About the U.S. Country Studies
Program</A></H2>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="description"><i><b>Program Description and
Objectives</B></I></A></H3>
<H5>The U.S. Country Studies Program provides financial and
technical assistance to developing and transition countries for
climate change studies.  The program was announced by the
President prior to the United Nations Conference on
Environment and Development<A
HREF="http://infoserver.ciesin.org/datasets/unced/unced.html">
(UNCED)</A> in Brazil in 1992.  The first round of two-year
studies began in October 1993, and a second round followed in
October 1994.  <A HREF="country.html">Fifty-five countries</A> on
five
continents currently participate in the program.  Regional and
sectoral oversight for
this program is provided by the U.S. Country Studies Management
Team (CSMT). Each participating
country has both a U.S. Project Officer and its own Country Study
Coordinator. For a list of these country project contacts, see
the <A HREF="sc.html">Country Contacts</A> list.

<P>The participating countries are developing inventories of
their anthropogenic emissions of greenhouse gases, assessing
their vulnerabilities to climate change, evaluating response
strategies for mitigating and adapting to climate change,
formulating national climate change action plans, and performing
technology assessments. If you would like more information about
a specific sector or region, contact the <A
HREF="cspstaff.html">(CSMT)</A>.<BR>
<P>The program provides technical assistance to countries through
<A HREF="workshop.html">workshops</A>, guidance documents and
analytical tools, and consultations with technical experts.
<P>The objectives of the program are to assist countries as
they:<UL>
<LI>establish a process for developing and implementing
national policies and measures, including formulation of National
Communications
<LI>develop information to further national and international
discussions
<LI>support principles and objectives of the U.N. Framework
Convention on Climate Change</UL>
<P>The program recently initiated a new activity to help
countries prepare national climate change action plans and to
conduct technology assessments.  This component of the program
will support countries' efforts to build on the results of their
current studies in the compilation of their national
communications, which are required by the United Nations
Framework Convention on Climate Change.  It also enables
countries to conduct in-depth evaluations of climate change
technology needs and opportunities to promote technology
diffusion.

<P>To help identify measures for these plans, countries will
conduct in-depth evaluations of potential applications and
markets for key energy and non-energy technologies. These
assessments will allow countries to develop suitable projects and
programs to promote the diffusion of these technologies.</H5>
<P>
<H6>Return to <A HREF="webpage.html"><I>Home Page</I></A></H6>
<P>
<P>
<HR>
<H3><I><A NAME="nextphse.html">Next Phase: Support for National
Action Plans (SNAP)</A></I></H3><BR>
<P><H5> Nine countries are currently participating in the
"Support for National Action Plans (SNAP)" phase of the U.S. CSP.

These countries are China, Czech Republic, Egypt, Indonesia,
Mexico, Micronesia, Philippines, Russia, and Venezuela.  The
program will provide technical and financial support for the
preparation of National Action Plans to additional countries in
1996. These countries are Bangladesh, Bolivia, Bulgaria, Hungary,
Kazakstan, Tanzania, Thailand, Ukraine, and Uruguay. In this
phase the countries will prepare national climate
change action plans and perform technology assessments.
<P>
<P>National Climate Change Action Plans describe specific
policies and programs that countries will implement to reduce
anthropogenic GHG emissions, preserve GHG sinks, and adapt to the
potential impacts of climate change. The plan will describe
national economic and environmental impacts of these actions, and
include an implementation strategy that addresses the integration
of the plan with other national environmental or development
plans. Under the UNFCCC developed nations are required to prepare
and submit a national action plan as part of their national
communications to the FCCC Secretariat. Developing countries have
more flexibility on the content and schedule for their
communications, with most developing country communications due
in 1997 and 1998.
<P>
<HR>
<P>

<P>Return to <A HREF="webpage.html"><I>Home Page</I></A> or view
information for the<A HREF="cspstaff.html"> CSMT </A>or for the <A
HREF="sc.html">Country Contacts</A>.</H6>
</body></html>
