<title>New Publications</title>
</head>
<body>
<a href = "http://gcrio.ciesin.org/"><img align = bottom src = "/gifs/gcrio-header.gif"></a>
<hr>
<h1>New Publications Available from the GCRIO</h1>
The publications described below are now available from the GCRIO.  
You may request a document by sending a message to 
help@gcrio.org, or by contacting GCRIO User Services at:<p>
<blockquote>
GCRIO User Services<br>
2250 Pierce Road<br>
University Center MI 48710<br>
Phone:  (517) 797-2730<br>
Fax:  (517) 797-2622<p>
</blockquote>
The GCRIO has a number of other global change documents available 
for distribution.  You can search our <a 
href="gopher://gopher.gcrio.org/11/GCRIO/holdings/">document 
holdings</a> to see what is available.<p>

<hr width=65% size=3>
<h2>20 September 1995</h2>

<h2>Forum on Global Change Modeling</h2>

On 12-13 October 1994, a <a href=/ipcc/cover.html>Forum on Global Change 
Modeling</a> was held at the
invitation of the Subcommittee on Global Change Research (SGCR) to help
address requests from the White House Office of Science and Technology
Policy (OSTP) and from Congressman Dingell to the General Accounting
Office (GAO).<p>

The charge to those contributing to the Forum was to develop a brief statement
on the credibility of projections of climate change provided by General
Circulation Models (GCMs) as background for potential interpretation of model
results in the context of developing and considering national policy
options.  The focus of this effort was specifically on the climate
aspects of the entire global change issue - thus not on the emission
scenarios, the consequences of change to ecosystems and natural resource
systems, or the socio-economic implications and potential for responses.<p>

<hr width=65% size=3> 
<h2>2 August 1995</h2>

<h2>The U.S. Global Change Data and Information System 
Implementation Plan</h2>

Global change research activities generate and require massive 
amounts of highly diverse data and information.  These data and 
information are needed to document change, to improve 
understanding of global change processes, and to carry out integrated 
assessments of impacts on human affairs.  The Global Change Data 
and Information System (GCDIS) is being developed to archive, 
preserve and make available the vast amount of data on all aspects 
of global change.  The GCDIS is the set of individual Federal agency 
data and information systems linked together to make global change 
data easily accessible to researchers and others.<p>

The <a href=/GCDIS/iplan/tocgcdip.html>U.S. 
Global Change Data and Information System 
Implementation Plan</a> describes the specific interagency 
agreements and arrangements established to implement the GCDIS.  
The plan also discusses the services (for example, guides to data or 
data browsing capabilities) that will be available to users.  A 
comprehensive overview of agency implementation activities, and a 
schedule of reaching overall goals are presented in the <a 
href=/GCDIS/iplan/tocgcdip.html>GCDIS 
Implementation Plan</a><p>

The Federal agencies involved in the GCDIS are:<p>

<blockquote>
Department of Commerce<br>
Department of Defense<br>
Department of Energy<br>
Department of the Interior<br>
Environmental Protection Agency<br>
National Aeronautics and Space Administration<br>
National Science Foundation<br>
U.S. Department of Agriculture<p>
</blockquote>


<hr width=65% size=3>
<h2>The U.S. Interagency UV-Monitoring Network Plan</h2>

The <strong>U.S. Interagency UV-Monitoring Network Plan</strong> 
was developed by the USGCRP's Ultraviolet Radiation Panel 
Observations Working Group, which is comprised of Federal experts 
in UV monitoring and research, to:<p>
<ol><li>Establish guidelines for the U.S. Federal government UV-
monitoring community to ensure that the data collected at each site 
are accurate, intercalibrated and easily available to UV-data users 
through the use of common data archival and retrieval mechanisms.

<li>To inform decision makers, scientists, and other persons with an 
interest in U.S. Federal UV-radiation monitoring and research 
activities of the capabilities and plans of the agencies active in this 
field.</ol><p>

This plan is the first such integrated national plan for UV monitoring, 
and is the starting point for developing a national UV monitoring 
network.  The report includes:  An Executive Summary;   maps;  a 
listing of Members of the USGCRP UV Panel;   a Selected Reading List 
on UV Radiation Activities and Issues;  and, a listing of UV-related 
activity points of contact within the agencies of the USGCRP.<p>
<center>
