<html><head><!-- This document was created from RTF source by rtftohtml version
2.7.4 --><title>Introduction to Geoindicator Checklist</title></head><body><p>

<b>INTRODUCTION TO GEOINDICATOR CHECKLIST</b>
<p>
A.R. Berger<p>
<em>Chairman, Geoindicators Working Group, Victoria, BC, Canada</em><p>
1  WHAT ARE GEOINDICATORS?<p>
Geoindicators are measures (magnitudes, frequencies, rates, and trends) of
geological processes and phenomena occurring at or near the Earth's surface and
subject to changes that are significant in understanding environmental change
over periods of 100 years or less. They measure both catastrophic events and
those that are more gradual, but evident within a human lifespan. Geoindicators
can be used to monitor and assess changes in fluvial, coastal, desert, mountain
and other terrestrial areas. They can also be used through paleoenvironmental
research to unravel trends over the past few centuries and longer, thus
providing important baselines against which human-induced and natural stresses
can be better understood.<p>
	Geoindicators measure environmental change in terms that can be regarded as
significant within the time span considered - presumably, not in amounts as low
as parts per trillion (e.g. for contaminants) or as grams per square km
(erosion), or rates as slow as a few mm per 1000 years (e.g. sea-levels). As
defined, they do not apply to important earth processes that generally take
place more slowly, such as diagenesis, metamorphism and deformation, and plate
tectonic movements.<p>
	Geoindicators describe processes and environmental parameters that are capable
of changing without human interference, though human activities can accelerate,
slow or divert natural changes (e.g. Goudie 1990a, Turner et al. 1990). Humans
are certainly an integral part of nature and the environment, but it is
essential to recognize that nature and the environment are ever changing at one
temporal and spatial scale or another, whether or not people are present.
Environmental sustainability must, therefore, be assessed against a potentially
moving background. <a href= "table1.gif">Table 1</a> indicates the relative influence of human and
natural (non-anthropogenic) stresses on geoindicators, though it excludes from
consideration indirect changes brought about by global-scale, human-induced
climate change. <a href= "table1.gif">Table 1</a> also identifies those geoindicators that can, by
reaching back into the recent geological past, help to establish the baseline
against which contemporary change can be assessed and future change forecast.
<p>
	Geoindicators have been developed from standard approaches used in geology,
geochemistry, geophysics, geomorphology, hydrology and other earth sciences.
For the most part the expertise and technology already exists (e.g. Cooke &amp;
Doornkamp 1990, Goudie 1990b). Some geoindicators are complex and costly, but
many are relatively simple and inexpensive to apply.<p>
2  FOR WHAT PURPOSES HAVE GEOINDICATORS BEEN DESIGNED?<p>
<p>
Geoindicators have been developed during a three-year international project by
the Commission on Geological Sciences for Environmental Planning (International
Union of Geological Sciences). They are designed for use in environmental and
ecological monitoring, state-of-the-environment reporting, and general
assessments of environmental sustainability on local, national and
international scales. They help to answer four basic questions.<p>
<ol><li>What is happening in the environment? (conditions and trends)<p>
<li>Why is it happening? (causes, links between human influences 		and natural
processes)<p>
<li>Why is it significant? (ecological, economic and health effects)<p>
<li>What are we doing about it? (implications for planning and policy)</ol>
Building on the fast-growing literature on environmental indicators (e.g.
Hammond et al. 1995, Munasinghe & Shearer, 1995, World Bank 1995),
geoindicators are designed for earth scientists and other professionals
involved in environmental management and research. With their main focus on
abiotic processes and parameters, geoindicators complement the work of
ecologists and others concerned with biodiversity, ecosystem management, and
environmental impact assessment (e.g. Spellerberg 1991, Woodley et al. 1993).
<p>
	Geoindicators can be used in the assessment of a number of environmental
processes and issues of importance to a sustainable society (Hammond et al.
1995, Hodge et al. 1995). Some geoindicators, such as surface water quality,
are already standard in monitoring environments for human health (the
'geochemical environment'), and relative sea level and glacier fluctuations
have long been applied to questions of climate change. Other geoindicators
should find a place in assessing the effects of global and regional change on
terrestrial ecosystems and on land-sea interactions. It is expected that
geoindicators will also be used for specific environmental concerns and issues,
such as those associated with forestry, agriculture, urban growth,
non-renewable resource extraction, and coastal zone management. <a href= "table2.gif">Table 2</a> relates
geoindicators to many of the major issues identified in Agenda 21 (UNCSD 1995).
Three additional concerns for environmental planning and management not
explicitly identified by UNCSD are also included in <a href= "table2.gif">Table 2</a>: ecosystem health
and integrity; mining, oil and gas developments; and reservoirs, dams,
irrigation systems and canals.<p>
<p>
<p>
3  THE GEOINDICATOR CHECKLIST<p>
<p>
Twenty-seven geoindicators are presented below in the form of a checklist or
menu. Each is described in a standard format with sixteen fields, which are
individually explained in the checklist. Appropriate indicators can be selected
depending on the terrain and the environmental issues under consideration. <p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
4  SELECTING GEOINDICATORS<p>
<p>
Because of the numerous efforts now being made in environmental monitoring and
reporting on land, this checklist concentrates on the terrestrial environment.
There are certainly important geoindicators of ocean and sea-floor processes,
such as thermal plumes, sediment de-gassing, fluid venting, seismicity,
subduction, turbidity currents and `black smokers' (sea-floor vents), and
future geoindicator projects may extend to the marine realm. Several
geoindicators in the present list deal with coastal environments, and one -
coral chemistry and growth patterns - applies equally to coastal and offshore
settings.<p>
	Geoindicators focus on abiotic components of the landscape and the associated
physical and chemical processes. However, biological and geological systems
interact intimately in time and space, so that it is not possible to ignore
living organisms. This is especially so when dealing with corals, deposits of
organic origin such as peat and soil, the influence of animals and plants on
weathering, erosion and deposition (Thomas 1990), or the role of microbiota
which can play a mediating role in groundwater chemistry and karst processes.
<p>
	It might be argued that tree-rings and lichens should have been included as
geoindicators, since both have an important role in dating geological deposits
and processes. This may well be done when the present checklist is revised.
Corals are also commonly regarded as bioindicators, but they are included here
for their use, through geochemical analysis, as a source of a wide range of
paleoenvironmental information, and not for their utility for chronological
analysis.<p>
	In developing geoindicators, the approach used was to identify a minimum set
of parameters which collectively describes the most important, short-term
dynamics of common landscapes and geological settings. In doing so, certain
geoindicators can be regarded as `high-level' or `integrative' (Munasinghe
&amp; Shearer 1995) - indicators that group related but independent measures.
Other geoindicators are `proxy' indicators that represent a myriad of other
parameters on which they depend.<p>
	Shoreline position is an example of a geoindicator that can act, at least
partially, as a proxy for local sea level, coastal subsidence, or wave climate.
Seismicity may be taken as a proxy for the release of earth stresses. An
example of a `high-level' geoindicator is frozen ground activity. This groups
many important soil and surface processes and changes in permafrost areas,
including frost heaving, thermokarst, and active layer thickness.<p>
	Another `high-level' indicator, groundwater quality illustrates the
difficulties of choosing a few parameters in a world containing in excess of
10,000 potential contaminants produced by modern societies. These chemical
components and other, natural, ones may vary independently, and any one, alone
or in combination with others, may affect the health and functioning of humans
and other organisms. There does not seem to be a ready method to combine or
aggregate into one simple index the many chemical parameters that are important
for monitoring groundwater. For example, Cl reflects inorganic waste, HCO<SUB>3</SUB> the
extent of microbial activity in degrading organic pollution, and dissolved
organic carbon (DOC) can be a proxy for total organic pollutants, though this
is hard to measure at the low levels that are important for biological
functions (0.1-10 micrograms/l). There is as yet no way to measure total
pesticides. Moreover, aggregating the chemical parameters could be dangerous to
policy making, because specific chemicals that are potentially harmful could
easily be overlooked. The decision was, therefore, to define groundwater
quality as including salinity; pH; redox status; fluoride in drinking water;
radioactivity; NO<SUB>3</SUB>; K/Na, PO<SUB>4</SUB>, herbicides, pesticides and insecticides; SO<SUB>4</SUB>,
As, F, Sr, metals; and HCO<SUB>3</SUB>, DOC, B, and solvents. <p>
	The boundaries between geoindicators and other, non-geological, measures of
environmental change and quality are not sharp, and some rather arbitrary
choices were made in compiling this first checklist. For example, many chemical
parameters needed to assess the quality of both surface and groundwater are
included, because of the interdependency of surface water with other parts of
the hydrological cycle: groundwater quality, streamflow, soil and sediment
erosion, and even soil quality, karst activity, and wetlands water budget and
geochemistry. On the other hand, the checklist excludes snow cover, which is an
important determinant for runoff, soil moisture, soil creep, solifluction,
frost action and avalanches. <p>
<p>
5  OTHER POTENTIAL GEOINDICATORS<p>
<p>
Because they are of rather restricted significance for assessing the health of
the environment, certain geological processes and phenomena that are liable to
perceptible change in years or decades have not been included in the present
checklist:<p>
<p>
5.1 <em>Geomagnetic field and other geophysical parameters</em><p>
<p>
The Earth's magnetic field fluctuates in intensity and direction in terms
measurable on the time scale of geoindicators. Because the effect of these on
ecosystems are unknown, and because the magnetic field is well monitored now on
a global scale (e.g. for navigation and power transmission), magnetic
variations have been omitted. Some other geophysical properties (e.g.
electrical) may undergo rapid change. For example, rock permeability may change
rapidly in certain dynamic environments, such as seismic zones, hydrothermal
regions, or sites for wastes with high-levels of radioactivity or toxicity. If
so, there are implications for groundwater flow, the spread of contaminants, or geothermal heat flow.<p>
<p>
5.2 <em>Rock stresses</em><p>
<p>
These are important mainly to engineering works where flat-lying rocks are
quarried (pop-ups), where the sides of excavations for building and tunnels are
squeezed, or where stresses are released in tunnels or mines (bumps, rock
bursts - associated in some coal fields with the sudden release of gas).
However, away from seismically-active areas, short-term fluctuations (`noise')
in regional stress intensity and pattern would probably be too great to allow
long-term trends to be identified. <p>
5.3 <em>Rock weathering</em><p>
<p>
On certain rock types the effects of geological processes, such as weathering,
and environmental stresses, such as acidification and air pollution, may be
determined where rock surfaces are dateable (e.g. old stone buildings,
tombstones). However, the effects are difficult to generalize to other kinds of
rocks and soils, but the development of rock varnish and other coatings on bare
rock surfaces might be taken as indicators of air temperature and chemistry. <p>
5.4 <em>Rock-microbe interactions</em><p>
<p>
Mineralogical processes mediated by microbial activity could be vulnerable to
environmental change (temperature, rainfall), with the results recorded in
speleothem growth, bacterial leaching, or travertine deposition. <p>
5.5 <em>Swelling of clays and soils</em><p>
<p>
Red clays formed as a result of weathering of carbonate rocks, and expansive
soils containing hydrophilic minerals, such as montmorillonite and illite,
commonly swell when absorbing water and shrink during drying. Buildings and
other engineering works may be damaged by associated ground collapse or
expansion and landslides. In China, industrial, residential and office
buildings covering more than 10 million m2 have been damaged or destroyed as a
result of swelling soils (Guo 1991).<p>
5.6 <em>Burning ground</em><p>
<p>
Fires in near-surface coal and peat deposits may be long-lasting and of obvious
importance to local ecosystems. Some are undoubtedly started by human actions,
but many are the result of spontaneous combustion or forest fires. Hot
sulphurous gases emitted from coastal mudstones in the Canadian Arctic have
been observed since 1826. In northern China, spontaneous combustion of coal
deposits is common, in part because of high geothermal heat flow associated
with crustal movement, and in part due to the oxidation of exposed coal
seams.<p>
5.7 <em>De-gassing of lake and marine sediments</em><p>
<p>
In seismic images of offshore and nearshore sediments, pockets of methane and
gas hydrates are commonly seen as diffuse patches disrupting regular seismic
reflectors. The release of these gases on land or beneath the sea may be
associated with the formation and activity of mud volcanoes, and surface heat
flow may be locally affected. Moreover, it has been suggested that gas bursts
at sea, whether of gas hydrate or volcanic origin, can cause sudden reduction
of ocean buoyancy with devastating effects on nearby vessels. In coal mines,
sudden bursts of methane gas, commonly mixed with CO<SUB>2</SUB> and N, are a major hazard
to underground operations and the cause of many mining disasters.  <p>
6  EARTH RESOURCES AS INDICATORS<p>
<p>
The inclusion in the checklist of geoindicators that assess soil, surface water
and groundwater quality reflects the common emphasis on their suitability for
human use, with much less regard placed on the extent of the resource. However,
there are no geoindicators, as defined here, that describe changes in stocks of
non-renewable earth materials consumed by society (minerals, hydrocarbons).
This is because resource extraction and utilization is not a geological process
but a wholly human action on earth materials, most of which do not change
through natural processes on the geoindicator time scale. A project now
underway by SCOPE (the Scientific Committee on Problems of the Environment)
aims to assess the human contribution to global geomorphological change,
including earth materials moved in the course of mining and water extraction.
<p>
	A number of other geoindicators in the present checklist deal indirectly with
resource issues: glacier fluctuations as one cause of variations in the supply
of water to rivers, groundwater levels as a measure of the availability of
sub-surface water for use by society, or wetlands as a source of peat for fuel
and horticulture. It would not be difficult to extend the geoindicator concept
to measure the extent of resource (minerals, rocks, energy, water) extraction
and usage, including processing and recyling. Indeed, many national economic
accounting systems already include such indicators as (human-induced) changes
in mineral and fossil fuel reserves, rate of extraction, processing, usage, and
recycling. <p>
7  DISCUSSION<p>
7.1 <em>A matter of priorities</em><p>
On a regional or global scale, some geoindicators are clearly more important
than others. It is not difficult, for example, to rank soil and water quality
indicators well ahead of subsurface temperature regime or desert surface
crusts. However, apart from the mention in individual entries of some
subsidiary indicators as primary or secondary (see groundwater quality,
shoreline position), there is no prioritizing in this checklist. The approach
has been to specify geoindicators that are important for specific environments,
not to rank deserts (dune, dust storm, surface crusts and fissures) or coral
reefs in importance relative to coastal zones or permafrost regions.<p>
7.2  <em>Interconnections</em><p>
The fact that geoindicators relate to (earth) systems makes their
categorization difficult. Indeed, one problem in erecting such a checklist is
that the inevitable impression is given of separate environmental compartments
with little interaction. This is certainly not the case: chemical loads and
fluctuations in surface water and groundwater, sediments, soils, biota and the
atmosphere are intimately linked, and variations in one affect others.
Moreover, as stated earlier, natural patterns are commonly overridden by human
influences. For example, coastal subsidence (the surface displacement
geoindicator) may be part of the same overall situation - say in the
Mississippi River delta region - that involves changes in river channel
morphology (streamflow and stream channel morphology), loss of nearby wetlands
(wetlands extent, structure, water budget and geochemistry), river sediment
load (stream sediment storage and discharge), local sea level (relative sea
level), and the morphology and location of the shore (shoreline position).
Nevertheless, there is a need to start at some simple and basic level. The
checklist can, thus, be regarded as a kind of landscape metric, the purpose of
which is to facilitate the monitoring of geological processes and parameters
which may be important to the well-being and sustainability of environments,
ecosystems and human settlements.<p>
	The approach used in this checklist for assessing fluctuations in
environmental geochemistry and its effects on ecosystems and humans is through
geoindicators related to the `quality' of two major earth media, water and
soils, with special reference to groundwater and surface water systems,
wetlands, and karst processes. A different approach, used extensively in
large-scale modelling of earth systems, is based on geochemical cycles - the
movement through the lithosphere, hydrosphere, biosphere, and atmosphere of
metals, gases, trace elements and other key chemical components. It would,
thus, be possible to separate out individual components and to assess changes
in their concentrations (flux) in various media in terms of effects on
ecosystems, thresholds, causes, and so forth. Sulphur, oxygen, phosphate,
mercury, copper, radon etc. could each be listed. This approach is immensely
more complex in terms of the number of possible components to be dealt with
separately. It also runs the risk of missing important interactions between
environmental compartments and processes. <p>
7.3 <em>Combining geoindicators</em><p>
Some geoindicators are simple, specific measures that can be represented on a
map so as to be immediately understandable by non-specialists. Shoreline
position and the lake areal extent are two such examples. They can reflect
climate change, human interference or both (as in the familiar images of the
much diminished Aral Sea, with fishing boats abandoned on the dried-up lake
bed). In contrast, soil and groundwater quality, which depend on many separate
components, are far more difficult to represent.  It would be convenient to
group geoindicators into one overall parameter or index, in the way that
economists, for instance, represent the national value of goods and services,
imports and exports, by GNP or GDP. Decision- and policy-makers commonly demand
simple environmental measures - a few indicators that will tell them, and the
general public, what progress is being made towards environmental
sustainability.  However, there does not seem to be an obvious way to do this,
and one may well question the wisdom of trying to represent open natural
systems by single measures.<p>
7.4 <em>The question of natural hazards </em><p>
Geoindicators measure processes that produce perceptible results within a
century. They are concerned more with the build-up to such singular events as
earthquakes and volcanic eruptions, rather than the events themselves. It
should be noted that change in many geoindicators takes place during
infrequent, extreme events (e.g. floods, sinkhole collapse, landslides,
eruptions, faulting), which are difficult to capture by routine monitoring.<p>
	Geoindicators are not directly concerned with mitigating the effects of
natural disasters. Thus, a volcanic eruption is not itself an indicator in the
sense used here, but rather a particular expression of a continuing natural
process, volcanicity. The volcanic unrest geoindicator describes the thermal,
structural, and geomorphological state of a region liable to erupt. Likewise, a
single earthquake is not a geoindicator: the well-known seismicity geoindicator
reflects the state of stress and its release within specific regions of the
Earth's crust, which may or may not lead to an obvious earthquake. Tsunamis,
those seismically-generated waves that can produce so much damage to coastal
areas, are not geoindicators, and neither are landslides, per se, but rather
the state of slopes likely to fail. Parameters that assess soil erosion are
included, but a single river flood is not - though the frequency of flooding is
implicit in the streamflow geoindicator.<p>
7.5 <em>Geoindicators as automatic recording stations</em><p>
Some geoindicators have the capacity to record and store evidence of
environmental changes. Examples include speleothem growth patterns (karst
activity), ice layers, subsurface temperature regimes, lake sediment
geochemistry, and corals. Though their main value is as paleoclimatic archives,
they have an important application to long-term monitoring of environments
where it is not possible, for reasons of cost, personnel or remoteness, to
install recording instruments. Such geoindicators provide `automatic recording
stations' that can be invaluable as registers of contemporary environmental
change, for they function without human intervention, even if de-coding the
record is sometimes costly (see review by Glen in Berger and Iams 1996). They can, to a degree, be regarded as comparable to
weather or seismic stations, which record their data on tapes that are
collected from time to time and shipped off for analysis.  Such natural
recording stations can be sampled at intervals to determine how their
environment has changed.  Thus, one may revisit a remote lake every decade to
extract a ten-year record from the sediment layer of airborne particulates or
of changes in watershed erosion rate. The near-surface thermal profile beneath
an abandoned forest clear-cut could be used to determine a record of recent
changes in soil temperature.<p>
7.6  <em>The pressure-state-response approach to indicators</em><p>
The format used here for listing geoindicators does not follow the
pressure-state-response framework, which in one form or another is now being
applied to a wide range of  environmental and `sustainability' indicators (e.g.
Hammond et al. 1995, World Bank 1995). In this approach, targeted largely at
managers and decision-makers, indicators are developed to assess <p>
<ol><li>stresses on the environment due to human activity, 
<li>the resulting condition or state of the environment, and
<li>the policy response to correct undesirable situations.</ol> 
The difficulty with this scheme is that the condition of most environments at
any time reflects, as emphasized earlier, not only human stresses but also
natural processes, which may be causing change whether or not people are
present. Clearly, harmful human stresses on the environment must be curbed but,
particularly in rural and wilderness areas, it may be extraordinarily difficult
to distinguish human actions that can be controlled from natural influences
that generally cannot (see Table 1). <p>
8  WHAT NEXT?<p>
The most effective test of the usefulness of geoindicators will be found in
their application to environmental monitoring programs. Many geological surveys
have long been active in this area, though they have not always worked closely
with biological, agricultural, forestry and other agencies. The challenge is to
ensure that earth systems addressed by geoindicators are included in integrated
monitoring programs and state-of-the-environment assessments. From such case
studies will come the information needed to test the relevance and value of
this new kind of landscape metric and to make the revisions to both the
checklist framework and detail that will undoubtedly be needed.<p>
	Many monitoring and modelling projects suitable for geoindicator application
are linked to local and national state-of-the-environment reporting or to the
Earthwatch activities of UNEP. One of the core projects of the International
Geosphere-Biosphere Program (IGBP) on Global Change is studying the effects of
climate change on terrestrial ecosystems. Another focuses on ocean-land
interactions in the coastal zone, and another on biospheric aspects of the
hydrological cycle. In understanding the effects of environmental change, there
are two other important dimensions to consider in addition to the global ones.
These are the natural landscape processes that work at a local level, and the
direct, near-at-hand effects of human activities. Clearly all three (global,
local natural, and local human) processes operate in many parts of the Earth,
even if separating their effects may not be possible in every situation.
Geoindicators, by providing another set of tools for assessing change, should
assist in this task.<p>
	There are several specific challenges for future work on geoindicators. One is
to define more closely the thresholds or critical loads involved, so that it
may be possible to express more specifically the relative stability of a
particular environment. Indeed, if for each indicator there were targets set by
environmental policy (e.g. Adriaanse 1993), or clear thresholds or limits that
once crossed would require policy action, the process of aggregating a
multitude of complex indicators to a small number of readily-understood,
higher-level indices (an environmental GDP or commodity market index) would be
facilitated. And if this could be done for a broad range of environmental
indicators, including those dealing with biodiversity and ecosystem integrity,
then it might be possible to combine these with simple measures describing some
of the important human dimensions of environmental change, the socio-economic
indicators of sustainability that are now much discussed. The danger of such an
approach is that a high-level sustainability index may suggest that the
environment and human systems are improving, whereas a destructive earthquake
or hurricane, warnings of which may not show up in such an index, could nullify
the improvements. <p>
	The whole area of environmental and sustainability assessment is in
considerable ferment, with new ideas fast developing. If geoindicators are to
keep pace with contributions from economics, environmental studies, ecology,
and other disciplines, it will be necessary to keep a watching brief on new
developments and to cooperate closely with others engaged in environmental
assessment. <p>
