<html>
<head>
<title>Department of Defense </title>
</head>
<body>
<a name=#A> </a>
<a href = "http://gcrio.ciesin.org/"><img align = bottom src = "/gifs/gcrio-header.gif"></a><br>
<hr><br>
<p align=left>
<h1>Department of Defense</h1>
<p>
<h2>Areas Of Global Change Research</h2>
<p align=left>
The US Department of Defense (DOD) provides unique capabilities and programs
that concurrently satisfy Defense mission requirements and USGCRP goals,
involving research in high latitude dynamics, regional resolving models,
boundary layer dynamics, and ocean ecological systems.  The DOD routinely
collects environmental data globally in support of DOD operations, and also
conducts mission-related research into environmental processes and conditions
that affect defense operations, tactics, and systems.   While the DOD does not
have a mission requirement to archive data for civil uses, DOD data products are made available to the appropriate US national archives for subsequent use by
the Global Change and Data Information System(GCDIS).
<p align=left>
<h2>Related Research</h2>
<p align=left>
In addition to a modest focused research program, DOD contributory research
addresses issues in the observation, understanding, and prediction of global
change, including: the observation and monitoring of unique middle and upper
atmosphere phenomena; the Heard Island follow-on project monitoring temperature profiles of the world oceans through acoustic topography; fundamental research to understand global change including programs in physical oceanography, ocean
biology, marine meteorology/air-sea interaction and solar influences; and,
several programs in predictive modeling of the ocean-atmosphere system where
primary emphasis is on ocean modeling at various scales, but also includes a
strong program in atmospheric dynamics and global cloud specification/modeling. 
<p align=left>
The Commander, Naval Meteorology and Oceanography Command, supports activities
that provide meteorological, oceanographic, and mapping, charting and geodetic
products for DOD and U.S. Navy operations.  Complete synoptic and aviation
meteorological observations, bathythermograph and Salinity-Temperature-Depth
(STD) casts, bathymetry, and limited biological observations are routinely
recorded.  The Defense Mapping Agency (DMA) is the DOD manager for mapping,
charting, and geodesy (MC&G) data around the world, and adopts or establishes
MC&G standards promoting interoperability within the DOD and with allies.  In
response to DOD requirements, the DMA complies, produces, reproduces, and
distributes maps, charts, and digital MC&G data.  These types of data aid in
determining watershed and shoreline changes, sea level rise, variations in
coastal currents, rates of urbanization, and changes in the extent of vegetated
areas.  Release of DMA data depends on security classification, level of
resolution, and any third-party restrictions that may be in effect.
<p align=left>
The Defense Technical Information Center (DTIC) is the central repository
within DOD for scientific and technical information generated in support of DOD research and development efforts.  The DTIC primarily serves the DOD, other
federal agencies, and their contractors.  The DTIC forwards to the National
Technical Information Service(NTIS) all DOD technical information provided by
DTIC to DOD organizations when cleared for public release.  The NTIS serves the
general public by providing access to these data for DOD and the other federal
research and development agencies.
<p align=left>
Research organizations including the Naval Research Laboratory, NASA, the Jet
Propulsion Laboratory, the NSF, Rand Corporation, the Army Engineering and
Topographic Lab, the Air Force Institute of Technology, and Rice University
provide global change information for DTIC to disseminate.  Information on
global change in DTIC's collection includes analytical reports about research
conducted, as well as data sets, models, projections, research proposals, and
summaries of research efforts.
<p align=left>
The Strategic Environmental Data Active Archive Resource (SEDAAR) is an
environmental analysis, remediation, and education tool developed by the
Consortium for International Earth Science Information Network (CIESIN) and the
Environmental Research Institute of Michigan (ERIM) under the Strategic
Environmental Research and Development Program (SERDP) through the auspices of
the Office of Naval Research.
<h2>Access Points</h2>
<p align=left>
<dl>
<dt>Defense Technical Information Center Home Page
<dd><a href="http://www.dtic.dla.mil/"> http://www/dtic.dla.mil</a>
<dd>(703) 767-8222
<dd>(800) CAL-DTIC
<p>
<dt>Strategic Environmental Research and Development Program (SERDP) Home Page
<dd><a href="http://iridium.nttc.edu/env/dod_serdp.html">http://iridium.nttc.edu/env/dod_serdp.html</a> 
<p>
<dt>Strategic Environmental Data Active Archive Resource (SEDAAR) Education Home Page
<dd><a href="http://192.195.231.22/">http://sedaar.edu.ciesin.org</a>
</dl>
<p>
<p align=left>
<center>
