<html>
<head>
<title>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</title>
</head>
<body>
<a name=#A> </a>
<a href = "http://gcrio.ciesin.org/"><img align = bottom src = "/gifs/gcrio-header.gif"></a><br>
<hr><br>
<p align=center>
<h1>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</h1>
<p align=left>
<h2>Areas Of Global Change Research</h2>
<p align=left>
The National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) is responsible for Earth science research from space, including those studies of broad scientific scope that study the planet as an integrated whole.  Associated efforts include related process studies; suborbital and ground-based studies; advanced remote-sensing instrument development; improvement of techniques for the transmission, processing, archiving, retrieval, and use of data; related scientific models; and other research activities in atmospheric, oceanographic, and land sciences.
<p align=left>
NASA research efforts in global change involve space-based studies of the Earth as an integrated system, including research and satellite programs studying atmospheric ozone, ocean surface winds, tropical precipitation, and the Earth's upper atmosphere. This space-based activity complements ongoing ground-based research programs in the observation, understanding and modeling of radiation, climate dynamics and hydrology; ecosystem dynamics and biogeochemical cycles; atmospheric chemistry; solid Earth science; and the processing, archiving, retrieval, dissemination and use of global change data. 
<p align=left>
<h2>Related Research</h2>
<p align=left>
NASA is responsible for Earth science research from space, including those studies of broad scientific scope that study the planet as an integrated whole.  Associated efforts include related process studies; suborbital and ground-based studies; advanced remote-sensing instrument development; improvement of techniques for the transmission, processing, archiving, retrieval, and use of data; related scientific models; and other research activities in atmospheric, oceanographic, and land sciences.
<p align=left>
Mission to Planet Earth (MTPE) is NASA's contribution to the USGCRP.  It 
is aimed at characterizing the Earth as a system in order to understand the global environment through studying long-term natural and anthropogenic changes.  Mission to Planet Earth 
has as its cornerstone the Earth Observing System (EOS).  The EOS is a long-term, interdisciplinary, and multidisciplinary research mission to study global-scale processes through simultaneous observations from a suite of instruments in low-Earth orbit and the establishment of the EOS Data and Information System (EOSDIS) to handle all NASA Earth science data including those from other space missions and from nonspace observations.  The Earth Science Data and Information System (ESDIS) Project (Code 505) at Goddard Space Flight Center (GSFC) is developing and operating the EOSDIS.
<p align=left>
The EOSDIS Version 0 (V0) Information Management System (IMS) allows users to locate, browse, and order data products residing at any of the nine Distributed Active Archive Centers (DAACs).  NASA also maintains the Global Change Master Directory (GCMD).
<p align=left>
<h2>Access Points</h2>
<p align=left>
<dl>
<dt>NASA Home Page	
<dd><a href="http://www.gsfc.nasa.gov/NASA_homepage.html">http://www.gsfc.nasa.gov/NASA_homepage.html</a>
<p>
<dt>Mission to Planet Earth Home Page	
<dd><a href="http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/mtpe">http://www.hq.nasa.gov/office/mtpe</a>
<p>
<dt>Earth Observing System Home Page	
<dd><a href="http://eos.nasa.gov">http://eos.nasa.gov</a>
<p>
<dt>EOSDIS/ESDIS Home Page	
<dd><a href="http://spsosun.gsfc.nasa.gov/ESDIShome.html">http://spsosun.gsfc.nasa.gov/ESDIShome.html</a>
<p>
<dt>EOSDIS V0 IMS Home Page	
<dd><a href="http://harp.gsfc.nasa.gov:1729/eosdis_documents">http://harp.gsfc.nasa.gov/v0ims</a>
<p>	  	
