<h2>U.S. Country Studies Program</h2><hr>

<center><dl><dt><strong>ANNOUNCEMENT 
<dt>AND CALL FOR PAPERS<p>

<dt>Eastern European Regional Workshop on Greenhouse Gas Emission 
Inventories</strong><p>

<dt>May 8-11, 1995
<dt>Thermal Hotel
<dt>Budapest, Hungary</dl></center><p>

The Eastern European Regional Workshop on Greenhouse Gas 
Emission Inventories is sponsored by the U.S. Country Studies 
Program (USCSP) and hosted by the Hungarian Ministry for 
Environment and Regional Policy and the Hungarian Electrotechnical 
Association Systemexpert Consulting Ltd.  It is one of a series of 
workshops organized by the USCSP to support countries in the 
development of greenhouse gas emission inventories, as required by 
the Framework Convention on Climate Change.  The workshops 
provide an international forum for the exchange of information 
among representatives of countries undertaking climate change 
country studies, researchers and experts on greenhouse gas 
emissions, and policy makers.<p>

The Eastern European Workshop, to be held in Hungary on May 8-11, 
1995, will focus on greenhouse gas emission inventories for Central 
and Eastern European countries and the Newly Independent 
Countries of the former Soviet Union.  Participants will have an 
opportunity to present results of their inventory work and to discuss 
issues related to greenhouse gas estimation methodologies.  
Presentations on both methodological issues and results of national 
assessments will be organized into five sectors: fossil fuel combustion 
for energy; energy production, transmission, and distribution; 
industrial processes, wastes, and solvents; agriculture; and forestry 
and land-use change.  Additional presentations by countries outside 
of the region, which have already completed their emission 
inventories, are included on the agenda and will serve as points of 
comparison.  Special workshop sessions will be devoted to such topics 
as reconciling national data systems with international data systems, 
coordinating CORINAIR and IPCC/OECD reporting conventions, and 
regional and interregional cooperation.  Several working groups will 
be set up to develop practical recommendations on major issues 
discussed at the workshop.

<h3>Conference Publications:</h3>

Papers presented at the workshop and summaries of working group 
sessions will be professionally published in a Workshop Proceedings.  
The proceedings will be hardbound and widely circulated to the 
international climate change community.  All papers will be subject 
to peer review at the workshop before inclusion in the Proceedings.  
Experts interested in submitting a paper should send an abstract to 
Alexei Sankovski by April 7.

<h3>Workshop Goals</h3>

<ul><li>Promote the exchange of information on participants' experience in 
preparing inventories and provide a forum for constructive 
discussion of available methodologies among country researchers and 
international experts.<p>

<li>Further the development of consensus on methods for improving the 
quality of input data and emission estimates.<p>

<li>Identify and discuss possible options for cooperation and 
coordination among countries and institutions involved in climate 
change studies in Eastern Europe.</ul><p>



<h3>Participants</h3>

<ul><li>Countries participating in the U.S. Country Studies Program.<p>

<li>Other countries assessing national greenhouse gas emissions.<p>

<li>International inventory experts.<p>

<li>Donor organizations.<p>

<li>Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC).<p>

<li>OECD, IEA and other international organizations.</ul>


<h3>Interpretation</h3>

Interpretation will be provided in English and in Russian.

<h3>Contact Information</h3>

For further information, please contact the workshop organizers:

<pre>Sandor Molnar
Director
Hungarian Electrotechnical Association
Systemexpert Consulting Ltd.
Mikoviny S. u. 2-4.
H-1037 Budapest, 
Hungary
Tel:  36-1-250-5078
Fax:  36-1-188-9713

Jack Fitzgerald
U.S. Country Studies Management Team
P.O. Box 63
1000 Independence Avenue, SW
Washington, D.C.  20585
USA
Tel:  202-426-0194
Fax:  202-426-1540

Alexei Sankovski
ICF Incorporated
1850 K Street, N.W., Suite 1000
Washington, D.C. 20006
USA
Tel:  202-862-1137
Fax:  202-862-1144</pre>
