<html><head><title>US Country Studies Program - The Climate Network Electronic 
Conference</title></head>
<body>
<H2><A NAME="climat-l"><B>The Climate Network Electronic
Conference</A><B></H2>
<P>
<H5>
<A HREF="#sign-up"> Sign-up</A> instructions are listed below.
<P>
<P>
<H3><B><I>About the Climate Network</I></B></H3>
The Climate Network is an electronic conference that was
established by the U.S. CSP and the U.S. Agency for International
Development (USAID) to provide a forum for developing countries
and countries with economies in transition to maintain ongoing
discussions about experiences they have had with climate change
studies, the development of national climate change action plans
and communications, and other related issues.
<P>

Topics may include:<UL><I>

<LI>Country Study Results

<LI>National Plans and Communications

<LI>Methodologies (Vulnerability & Adaptation, and Mitigation)

<LI>Mitigation and Adaptation Projects

<LI>Financing Issues

<LI>Technology Transfer

<LI>FCCC Negotiations

<LI>Donor Programs

<LI>Activities Implemented Jointly (AIJ)

<LI>Any other related topics that the participants would like to

discuss</UL></I>

<P>

The discussion is open to all countries involved in the U.S.
Country Studies Program and to any other developing or transition
country that would like to share in the discussion. Developed
countries and international organizations will be invited to
join only by request from current developing and transition
country Climate Network participants.

<P>

The U.S. Country Studies Management Team (CSMT) will manage the
Climate Network and provide a conference administrator who
will be responsible for signing up new subscribers and refining
the topics and procedures as necessary. The CSMT will
not be an active participant in the discussion, and will, as
needed, refer specific questions to available experts who might
be able to contribute helpful answers.

<P>
<P>

<H3><A NAME="sign-up"><B><I>Sign-up Instructions</B></I></A></H3>

<B><I>This network is designed to promote free and open exchange
of information and ideas among developing and transition
countries and is intended for exclusive use by those
countries. Developed countries and international organizations
will not be invited to join except on request from developing and
transition countries that are currently participating in the
Climate Network.</B></I> 

<P>If you are from a developing or transition country and would
like to subscribe to the Climate Network, simply send an email
to "listproc@info.usaid.gov" saying in the body of the email
(Don't use the quotation marks), and leaving the subject line
blank: <BR>

<P>

     subscribe Climate-L yourname

<P>
<P>
<HR>
<P></H5>

