<h2>U.S. Country Studies Program</h2><hr>
<center><strong>ANNOUNCEMENT
AND CALL FOR PAPERS</strong><p>

<b><dl><dt>African Regional Workshop on Greenhouse Gas 
<dt>Emission Inventories and Emission Mitigation Options:
<dt>Forestry, Land-Use Change, and Agriculture</dl></b><p>

<dl><dt>29 May - 2 June 1995 
<dt>Aloe Ridge Hotel and Game Reserve
<dt>Johannesburg, South Africa</dl></center><p>

The African Regional Workshop on Greenhouse Gas Emission 
Inventories and Emission Mitigation Options is cosponsored by the 
U.S. Country Studies Program (USCSP) and the United Nations 
Environment Program (UNEP).  It is one of a series of workshops 
organized by USCSP to support countries in the development of 
greenhouse gas emission inventories and the evaluation of measures 
for responding to climate change, as required by the Framework 
Convention on Climate Change.  The workshops will provide an 
international forum for the exchange of information among 
representatives of countries undertaking climate change country 
studies, researchers and experts on greenhouse gas emissions and 
mitigation measures, and policy makers.  Participants will share and 
discuss the results of their work on national inventory preparation 
and mitigation assessment, and will have the opportunity to receive 
further guidance on these topics.<p>

This workshop, to be held in South Africa on May 29 to June 2, 1995, 
will focus on the development of emission inventories for the 
forestry, land-use change, and agriculture sectors in Africa.  There 
will also be presentations and discussions on options for reducing net 
emissions of greenhouse gases in these sectors.  These inventory and 
mitigation sessions will address both methodological issues and the 
results of national assessments.  Technical presentations will discuss 
data collection and emission factor determination for the relevant 
sectors: forestry and land-use change; vegetation burning; and 
livestock digestion and manure management.  Working group 
sessions will be held in order to facilitate discussion of methods and 
their application.  In addition, there will be sessions addressing 
regional cooperation and donor programs.<p>

<h3>Conference Publications</h3>

Papers presented at the workshop and summaries of working group 
sessions will be published in a Workshop Proceedings.  The 
Proceedings will be hardbound and widely circulated to the 
international climate change community.  All papers will be subject 
to peer review at the workshop before inclusion in the Proceedings.  
Experts interested in submitting a paper should send an abstract to 
Barbara Braatz by April 7.

<h3>Workshop Goals</h3>

<ul><li>Promote the exchange of information on participants' 
experience in preparing inventories and assessing mitigation options, 
and provide a forum for constructive discussion of available 
methodologies.

<li>Further the development of consensus among country researchers 
and international experts on emission estimation and mitigation 
assessment methods suitable for African countries.

<li>Clearly identify priority needs for support from potential donors 
in testing and using the methodologies.

<li>Identify and discuss possible options for mitigating emissions of 
greenhouse gases from non-energy sources in Africa.

<li>Promote cooperation and coordination among participants and 
institutions involved in climate change studies in Africa.</ul>

<h3>Participants</h3>

<ul><li>African countries participating in the U.S Country Studies Program 
and in UNEP's Country Case Studies on Sources and Sinks of 
Greenhouse Gases, sponsored by the Global Environment Facility 
(GEF).

<li>Other African countries interested in greenhouse gas emissions 
and emission mitigation options.

<li>International inventory and mitigation experts.

<li>Donor organizations.

<li>Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change.</ul>

<h3>Contact Information</h3>

For further information please contact the workshop organizers:

<pre>Jack Fitzgerald
